                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They shouted, \"Remember the Alamo!\" and used that failure as the fuel to win their independence.", start: 825.35, end: 830.05),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He contrasts this with the \"Chicken Littles\" of the world—the cynics who run around yelling, \"The sky is falling!\" whenever there is a rumor of a recession.", start: 830.89, end: 837.18),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He explains that cynics criticize, but winners analyze.", start: 837.76, end: 840.74),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Criticism blinds you; analysis opens your eyes.", start: 841.14, end: 843.82),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He tells the story of finding a great real estate deal, only to have a \"smart\" friend talk him out of it because \"prices might drop.\"", start: 844.36, end: 849.64),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The prices went up, and the friend stayed poor.", start: 850.08, end: 852.02),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The lesson?", start: 853.32, end: 853.72),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "\"Don't let the noise of the world drown out the whisper of opportunity.\"", start: 854.26, end: 857.5),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Algorithmic Doomer", start: 858.76, end: 859.82),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In 2026, the \"Chicken Littles\" have a megaphone.", start: 860.68, end: 863.76),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They are the algorithmic feeds on your phone, optimized to keep you terrified because fear drives engagement.", start: 864.18, end: 869.54),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The \"Inner Saboteur\" is now powered by AI-generated deepfakes and 24/7 \"Crash Coming Soon\" YouTube thumbnails.", start: 870.12, end: 876.8),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Laziness has also evolved.", start: 877.52, end: 878.86),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Today, laziness doesn't look like sleeping on the couch; it looks like \"busyness.\"", start: 879.22, end: 883.14),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You are too busy answering emails, checking Slack, and \"researching\" (watching tutorials) to actually do anything.", start: 883.62, end: 889.24),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This is \"productive procrastination.\"", start: 889.72, end: 891.62),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The modern winner ignores the comment section.", start: 892.28, end: 894.16),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They realize that if an investment feels \"safe\" to the herd, it’s already too late.", start: 894.62, end: 898.58),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Saboteur tells you to wait for certainty.", start: 899.12, end: 901.08),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Wiser investor knows certainty is expensive.", start: 901.58, end: 904.1),
                ]),
            ],
            7: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Knowledge Coma", start: 918.62, end: 919.46),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Here is the final, most dangerous trap: You are smarter now.", start: 920.76, end: 924.58),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You have read the Cores.", start: 924.94, end: 925.8),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You understand the math.", start: 926.14, end: 927.16),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "And yet, tomorrow morning, you will likely wake up and do exactly what you did today.", start: 927.6, end: 932.0),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This is the \"Knowledge Coma.\"", start: 932.62, end: 933.94),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The friction isn't ignorance anymore; it is inertia.", start: 934.62, end: 937.48),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Most people collect financial advice like baseball cards—they categorize it, admire it, and show it off, but they never play the game.", start: 938.46, end: 945.47),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They are waiting for the \"perfect time\" or the \"perfect deal,\" unaware that perfection is just procrastination in a tuxedo.", start: 946.07, end: 952.19),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Power of \"I Don't Want\"", start: 953.37, end: 955.11),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author shatters this paralysis not with a spreadsheet, but with a piece of paper.", start: 956.23, end: 960.45),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He tells the story of how he found his \"Why\"—the fuel that outlasted his fear.", start: 961.11, end: 965.53),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He didn't start by writing down \"I want to be rich.\"", start: 966.13, end: 968.41),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "That was too vague.", start: 968.81, end: 969.59),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Instead, he sat down and ruthlessly listed what he didn't want.", start: 969.95, end: 973.47),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "\"I don't want to work for someone else for the rest of my life.\"", start: 974.19, end: 976.53),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "\"I don't want to be told when I can go on vacation.\"", start: 976.95, end: 978.97),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "\"I don't want to miss my child’s soccer game because of a conference call.\"", start: 979.41, end: 982.19),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He explains that this \"List of Don'ts\" created a pressure cooker of emotion.", start: 983.25, end: 987.13),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It wasn't just a wish; it was a rejection of mediocrity.", start: 987.59, end: 990.67),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This deep-seated emotional leverage—the \"Power of Spirit\"—is the only force strong enough to push you through the inevitable obstacles of the first 90 days.", start: 991.11, end: 999.13),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Without a burning \"Why,\" the \"How\" is useless.", start: 999.59, end: 1002.15),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The 2026 \"Micro-Step\" Revolution", start: 1003.27, end: 1005.43),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In 2026, the barrier to entry has collapsed.", start: 1005.81, end: 1009.03),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You don't need $50,000 for a down payment or a license to trade.", start: 1009.49, end: 1013.17),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The \"Launchpad\" today is built on micro-actions.", start: 1013.71, end: 1016.45),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author couldn't buy 0.0001% of a building in 1997.", start: 1017.02, end: 1020.74),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Today, you can.", start: 1022.1, end: 1023.04),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You can buy fractional shares of real estate, tokenized gold, or a slice of a startup for the price of a latte.", start: 1023.56, end: 1029.18),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The modern error is thinking you need to \"launch\" a massive enterprise.", start: 1030.74, end: 1034.32),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You don't.", start: 1034.66, end: 1035.02),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You need to launch a habit.", start: 1035.48, end: 1036.94),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The \"Wiser\" approach uses automation to bypass your willpower entirely.", start: 1037.54, end: 1041.48),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You don't \"decide\" to invest; you set up a smart contract or an auto-debit that invests for you before you even wake up.", start: 1042.04, end: 1048.08),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You build the wealth architecture once, and then you let the machine run.", start: 1048.58, end: 1052.4),
                ]),
            ],
        ],
        2: [
            1: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Illusion of Competence", start: 7.94, end: 9.4),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Here is the uncomfortable truth: 90% of people who think they are \"investing\" are actually just gambling with better odds.", start: 9.86, end: 17.64),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The friction in your financial life usually stems from a single category error.", start: 18.32, end: 22.74),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You treat the stock market like a casino where the chips are expensive and the rules are vague.", start: 23.38, end: 28.06),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You assume that because you bought a stock and held it for a year, you are an investor.", start: 28.54, end: 32.5),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You aren't.", start: 32.98, end: 33.64),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you bought it based on a feeling, a tip, or a chart pattern, you are speculating.", start: 34.24, end: 38.82),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "And the market loves to punish speculators who believe they are investors.", start: 39.28, end: 43.22),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Trinity of Safety", start: 43.76, end: 45.03),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author solves this by demanding we sign a mental contract before spending a dime.", start: 45.79, end: 50.39),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He strips away the noise and offers a ruthless definition.", start: 50.87, end: 54.61),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "An operation is only an investment if it meets three specific criteria upon thorough analysis:", start: 55.33, end: 61.07),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Safety of Principal: You are reasonably sure you won't lose your initial cash.", start: 61.85, end: 66.13),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Adequate Return: You aren't looking for a lottery ticket; you are looking for a fair rent on your money.", start: 66.61, end: 71.89),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Thorough Analysis: You have done the math on the underlying business, not just the stock price.", start: 72.49, end: 78.13),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Imagine a man betting on a horse race.", start: 78.63, end: 80.75),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He studies the track record, the jockey, and the weather.", start: 81.23, end: 83.95),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He is informed, but he is still gambling because he has no safety of principal—if the horse loses, his money vanishes.", start: 84.45, end: 91.35),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The \"Intelligent Investor\" refuses to bet on the horse; he buys the racetrack.", start: 91.79, end: 97.13),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Gamification Trap", start: 97.51, end: 98.81),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In the modern era, this distinction is harder to see because the casino has moved into your pocket.", start: 99.35, end: 104.57),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Trading apps shower you with digital confetti when you execute a trade, conditioning you to crave action over analysis.", start: 105.57, end: 112.79),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We see this in the \"Crypto Craze\" or the \"AI Gold Rush.\"", start: 113.41, end: 116.83),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Buying a digital token because you hope a billionaire tweets about it is not investing; it is the \"Greater Fool Theory\"—hoping someone else will pay more for your mistake.", start: 117.83, end: 126.71),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The danger today isn't just market volatility; it’s the user interface of your life designed to make speculation feel like strategy.", start: 127.63, end: 135.06),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If your asset relies entirely on hype to succeed, you aren't investing in a business; you're investing in a narrative.", start: 135.84, end: 143.28),
                ]),
            ],
            2: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Safety Paradox", start: 181.66, end: 182.74),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The greatest trick the financial industry ever pulled was convincing you that cash is \"safe.\"", start: 183.48, end: 188.72),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You look at your bank account, and the number stays the same or grows slightly.", start: 189.46, end: 193.08),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You feel a warm sense of security.", start: 193.74, end: 195.48),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You sleep well.", start: 196.0, end: 196.8),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But this is a hallucination.", start: 197.14, end: 198.42),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In the physical world, if you left a car in a garage for twenty years, you’d expect it to rust.", start: 198.88, end: 204.2),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Money is no different, yet we treat it as if it’s immune to decay.", start: 204.68, end: 208.32),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The friction here is psychological: we are wired to fear the volatility of the stock market (where prices bounce up and down visibly), so we run into the arms of a guaranteed loss.", start: 209.04, end: 218.98),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We choose the slow bleed over the bumpy ride.", start: 219.5, end: 221.65),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Yardstick That Shrank", start: 221.97, end: 223.27),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author illustrates this with a brutal reality check from the first half of the 20th century.", start: 223.91, end: 228.81),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He tells the story of the \"Conservative Investor\" who, traumatized by market crashes, put 100% of his wealth into high-grade bonds.", start: 229.45, end: 238.03),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This man felt prudent.", start: 238.61, end: 239.89),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He collected his fixed interest checks like clockwork.", start: 240.47, end: 243.27),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But while he was staring at the stable numbers on his statements, the world around him changed.", start: 243.69, end: 248.17),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The price of bread, housing, and energy doubled.", start: 248.81, end: 251.83),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The \"yardstick\" of money had shrunk.", start: 252.35, end: 254.05),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author points out that by the time this investor needed to spend his principal, it had lost half its purchasing power.", start: 254.59, end: 260.79),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The man hadn't lost dollars; he had lost lifestyle.", start: 261.55, end: 264.25),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The \"safe\" investment was actually a trap that guaranteed he would be poorer at the end than when he started.", start: 264.77, end: 271.43),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author’s lesson is stark: Inflation is a thief that works in the dark, and keeping all your money in \"safe\" cash is not prudence—it is a decision to let the thief empty your house while you watch.", start: 272.11, end: 283.37),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The High-Yield Hallucination", start: 283.87, end: 285.21),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Today, this enemy is even more deceptive.", start: 285.57, end: 288.63),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You open a High-Yield Savings Account (HYSA) offering 5% and think you are winning.", start: 289.17, end: 294.81),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You aren’t.", start: 295.39, end: 295.99),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You are barely treading water.", start: 296.47, end: 297.89),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If inflation is running at 3.5% and the tax man takes another 1.5% of your gains, your real return is zero.", start: 298.47, end: 305.85),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You are running on a financial treadmill just to stay in the same place.", start: 306.41, end: 309.72),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Furthermore, the \"basket of goods\" has changed.", start: 310.28, end: 312.9),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author worried about the price of milk; you need to worry about the cost of healthcare, college tuition, and prime real estate, which often inflate significantly faster than the government's official CPI numbers.", start: 313.5, end: 325.66),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you are paying 1% to a financial advisor to manage a portfolio of cash and bonds that yields 4%, you are essentially paying someone to manage your slow bankruptcy.", start: 326.3, end: 336.1),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In a world of unlimited fiat currency printing, holding cash is like holding a melting ice cube.", start: 336.7, end: 342.46),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You cannot save your way to wealth in a currency that is designed to depreciate.", start: 342.92, end: 347.28),
                ]),
            ],
            3: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Price Tag Panic", start: 354.62, end: 355.78),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Imagine you own a house you love.", start: 356.36, end: 358.34),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You know its value: good roof, solid foundation, great neighborhood.", start: 358.88, end: 362.66),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Now imagine a stranger stands on your lawn every single morning yelling a different price at you.", start: 363.28, end: 367.74),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Monday he screams, \"I'll give you $500,000!\"", start: 368.52, end: 370.36),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Tuesday he whispers, \"The market is crashing!", start: 372.28, end: 374.92),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "I'll only give you $150,000!\"", start: 375.48, end: 376.06),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Wednesday he is euphoric again and offers $900,000.", start: 377.88, end: 380.14),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Most people would close the blinds and ignore him.", start: 381.92, end: 384.7),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But in the stock market, you do the opposite.", start: 385.12, end: 387.48),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You let this stranger dictate your emotional state.", start: 387.94, end: 390.64),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When he yells a low price, you panic and sell your house cheap.", start: 391.22, end: 394.74),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When he yells a high price, you feel rich and buy more houses.", start: 395.24, end: 398.88),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This is the friction: you confuse the price on the screen with the value of the business.", start: 399.44, end: 403.73),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You let the fluctuating price tag determine your worth, rather than the quality of the merchandise.", start: 404.25, end: 409.33),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Partner You Can't Fire", start: 409.83, end: 412.09),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author introduces us to this stranger.", start: 412.65, end: 415.05),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "His name is \"Mr.", start: 415.65, end: 416.65),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Market.\"", start: 417.13, end: 417.53),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He is your business partner in a private company.", start: 418.03, end: 420.37),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Mr.", start: 421.25, end: 421.59),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Market is obliging but emotionally unstable.", start: 422.07, end: 424.51),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Every day, without fail, he names a price at which he will either buy your interest or sell you his.", start: 425.11, end: 431.11),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The catch?", start: 431.57, end: 432.13),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "His price has nothing to do with the business's actual performance.", start: 432.55, end: 436.75),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It is based entirely on his mood.", start: 437.11, end: 439.01),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When he is manic (optimistic), he sees only sunshine and names a high price.", start: 439.55, end: 444.81),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When he is depressed (pessimistic), he sees only trouble and names a low price.", start: 445.49, end: 450.57),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author’s solution is a mindset shift: Mr.", start: 451.01, end: 453.81),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Market is there to serve you, not to guide you.", start: 454.93, end: 457.65),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You are not forced to deal with him.", start: 458.13, end: 459.75),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If his offer is ridiculous, you ignore him.", start: 460.35, end: 463.09),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If his offer is a bargain, you buy.", start: 463.65, end: 465.55),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If his offer is absurdly high, you sell.", start: 466.09, end: 468.83),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You are the adult in the room; he is the hysterical child.", start: 469.27, end: 472.33),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Algorithm of Anxiety", start: 472.89, end: 474.55),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Today, Mr.", start: 475.15, end: 477.17),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Market isn't just a guy on your lawn; he is in your pocket, buzzing every 15 minutes.", start: 477.67, end: 482.35),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He is the notification on your phone saying \"Bitcoin is down 10%\" or \"Nvidia hits all-time high.\"", start: 482.85, end: 489.09),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The modern Mr.", start: 489.61, end: 491.07),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Market is amplified by algorithms designed to trigger your dopamine and cortisol.", start: 491.81, end: 496.81),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Consider the \"Flash Crash\" or the meme-stock frenzy.", start: 497.39, end: 500.69),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "These are Mr.", start: 501.27, end: 502.11),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Market on steroids—millions of people reacting to a viral sentiment rather than business fundamentals.", start: 502.49, end: 508.44),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you own an S&P 500 ETF, you own the 500 biggest companies in America.", start: 508.84, end: 514.38),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Did the value of Coca-Cola or Microsoft actually drop 20% in a week because of a geopolitical rumor?", start: 515.16, end: 521.58),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "No.", start: 522.08, end: 522.18),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Their factories didn't burn down.", start: 522.88, end: 524.44),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Their customers didn't vanish.", start: 524.9, end: 526.56),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Only the price tag changed.", start: 527.1, end: 528.64),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you react to the notification, you are letting the algorithm trade against you.", start: 529.14, end: 533.52),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You must view volatility not as risk, but as the fee you pay for higher returns.", start: 534.02, end: 539.14),
                ]),
            ],
            4: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Myth of the Mastermind", start: 563.0, end: 564.76),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "There is a persistent lie in finance that \"effort equals return.\"", start: 565.18, end: 569.22),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In your job, if you work 80 hours a week, you get a promotion.", start: 570.04, end: 573.56),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In the stock market, if you work 80 hours a week analyzing charts, reading news, and tweaking your portfolio, you will likely underperform a dead person.", start: 574.1, end: 582.3),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The friction here is ego.", start: 582.76, end: 584.18),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You believe you are smarter than the market.", start: 584.92, end: 586.78),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You believe you can time the top and the bottom.", start: 587.46, end: 590.16),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You believe that \"doing nothing\" is lazy.", start: 590.72, end: 592.98),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But in investing, activity is the enemy of returns.", start: 593.66, end: 597.38),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The more you touch your portfolio, the more you incur fees, taxes, and emotional errors.", start: 598.08, end: 603.62),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The goal of the Fortress is to protect you from your own desire to be clever.", start: 604.12, end: 607.77),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The 50/50 Split", start: 608.25, end: 609.47),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author solves this by creating a specific category for people who want to get rich without making investing their second job: the \"Defensive Investor.\"", start: 609.85, end: 618.99),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He proposes a radical simplicity.", start: 619.55, end: 621.61),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Imagine a portfolio that is a perfect balance scale.", start: 622.21, end: 625.07),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "On one side, you have high-grade bonds (lending money to stable governments or corporations).", start: 625.61, end: 631.29),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "On the other side, you have a diversified list of leading common stocks (owning a piece of the economy).", start: 631.91, end: 637.37),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author suggests a baseline split of 50% stocks and 50% bonds.", start: 637.91, end: 643.75),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This is your \"Fortress.\"", start: 644.51, end: 645.97),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When the stock market crashes and people are jumping out of windows, your bonds hold their value, and your portfolio only drops half as much as the market.", start: 646.65, end: 654.55),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You sleep well.", start: 655.05, end: 655.75),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When the market booms and your neighbor is bragging about his gains, your stocks participate in the rally.", start: 656.33, end: 662.35),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You never fully lose, and you never miss out.", start: 662.77, end: 665.39),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The genius is in the maintenance: if stocks go up and become 60% of your portfolio, you simply sell some stocks and buy bonds to get back to 50/50.", start: 665.79, end: 673.87),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This forces you to do the one thing everyone fails at: sell high and buy low, automatically.", start: 675.49, end: 681.45),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Autopilot Advantage", start: 682.11, end: 683.71),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Today, building this Fortress is easier than the author could have ever dreamed.", start: 684.17, end: 688.51),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In his day, you had to buy individual bonds and pick 20 different stocks.", start: 689.33, end: 694.63),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Today, you can build the entire Fortress with two clicks using low-cost Index Funds or ETFs (Exchange Traded Funds).", start: 695.31, end: 703.28),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Instead of picking \"winners\" (which is hard), you buy the entire S&P 500 or a Total World Stock ETF.", start: 703.86, end: 710.66),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You own Apple, Microsoft, Amazon, and 4,000 other companies.", start: 711.32, end: 715.76),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If one goes bankrupt, you don't even notice.", start: 716.32, end: 718.7),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If a new AI giant emerges, you automatically own it.", start: 719.2, end: 722.34),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This is the \"Boglehead\" philosophy (named after Jack Bogle, who popularized index funds), which is the modern spiritual successor to Graham’s Defensive strategy.", start: 723.02, end: 732.48),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It accepts that you cannot predict the future, so you simply own the entire economy.", start: 733.06, end: 737.98),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It turns investing from a stress-inducing hunt for \"the next Bitcoin\" into a boring, reliable utility bill that pays you.", start: 738.66, end: 745.46),
                ]),
            ],
            5: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Hero Complex", start: 752.58, end: 753.64),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Here is the seduction: You believe that if you are smarter, faster, and read more news than your neighbor, you will make more money.", start: 754.14, end: 762.22),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You view the stock market as a test of your intelligence.", start: 762.82, end: 766.0),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This is the \"Hero Complex,\" and it is the fastest way to underperform.", start: 766.52, end: 770.96),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The friction is simple: you are not competing against your neighbor.", start: 771.5, end: 774.52),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You are competing against institutional algorithms that read every news headline in milliseconds and price it in before you’ve even unlocked your phone.", start: 775.28, end: 783.86),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you try to \"win\" by buying the same popular, high-growth companies everyone else loves, you are paying a premium for a consensus view.", start: 784.66, end: 792.78),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You are buying a Ferrari at full sticker price and hoping to sell it for a profit.", start: 793.22, end: 797.33),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "That isn't investing; that's wishful thinking.", start: 797.95, end: 800.69),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Negative Art", start: 801.29, end: 802.35),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author solves this by redefining what it means to be \"Enterprising.\"", start: 802.85, end: 806.59),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He clarifies that being an Enterprising Investor is not about taking more risk; it is about doing more work.", start: 807.37, end: 813.97),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It is a job description, not a personality type.", start: 814.65, end: 817.79),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author warns against the siren song of \"Growth Stocks\"—the companies that everyone knows are the future.", start: 818.65, end: 824.95),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He tells the story of the investor who buys the great companies of the era (like the radio or airline pioneers) and loses everything because the price was already bid up to perfection.", start: 825.49, end: 836.05),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Instead, the Enterprising Investor practices a \"negative art.\"", start: 836.55, end: 840.29),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They avoid the popular.", start: 840.79, end: 841.97),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They hunt in the scrap heap.", start: 842.57, end: 844.03),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They look for \"bargain issues\"—stocks selling for less than their working capital.", start: 844.63, end: 849.79),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They buy when the news is bad, the outlook is gloomy, and the crowd is selling.", start: 850.33, end: 854.43),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Enterprising Investor makes their money not by predicting the future, but by correcting the market's mistakes in the present.", start: 854.81, end: 861.05),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Edge of Discomfort", start: 861.53, end: 863.09),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In the modern era, the \"easy\" information is gone.", start: 863.59, end: 866.33),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You cannot find a bargain just by looking at a P/E ratio on Yahoo Finance because a million other people have seen it too.", start: 866.61, end: 873.77),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Today, the \"Enterprising\" edge is almost entirely psychological.", start: 874.33, end: 878.07),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It is the ability to endure social pain.", start: 878.63, end: 880.79),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Think about the collapse of Meta (Facebook) in 2022 or the energy sector when oil prices went negative in 2020.", start: 881.31, end: 888.73),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The \"Enterprising\" move wasn't to buy Nvidia when it was on every magazine cover; it was to buy the unloved, \"boring,\" or \"dead\" sectors when everyone else was chasing AI hype.", start: 890.29, end: 900.84),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you are buying a stock that makes you feel smart at a dinner party, you are likely overpaying.", start: 901.5, end: 906.3),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The modern Enterprising strategy often involves \"Deep Value\" or \"Special Situations\"—spinoffs, distressed assets, or small-cap companies too small for the big funds to touch.", start: 907.02, end: 917.6),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You are looking for the \"ick factor\"—assets that are fundamentally sound but temporarily hated.", start: 918.04, end: 923.5),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Protocol", start: 924.14, end: 924.78),
                ]),
            ],
            6: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Croupier's Cut", start: 947.38, end: 948.32),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The financial industry is built on a single, powerful myth: \"Investing is too complicated for you to do alone; you need an expert.\"", start: 949.02, end: 956.58),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "So, you hand your money to a mutual fund manager—a \"star\" in a suit who promises to navigate the market's storms.", start: 957.36, end: 964.08),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You pay them a 1% or 2% fee every year, regardless of whether they make you money or lose it.", start: 964.56, end: 970.9),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The friction here is mathematical, not emotional.", start: 971.62, end: 974.28),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "That 2% fee sounds small, but over 30 years, it can consume up to 40% of your total wealth.", start: 975.1, end: 982.08),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You are taking 100% of the risk, providing 100% of the capital, and giving away nearly half the upside to a manager who, statistically, will fail to beat the market anyway.", start: 982.84, end: 994.27),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You aren't hiring a guide; you're carrying a parasite.", start: 995.05, end: 997.61),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Rearview Mirror Trap", start: 998.09, end: 999.51),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author saw this coming decades ago.", start: 999.83, end: 1001.81),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He identified the fatal flaw in how mutual funds are sold: Performance Chasing.", start: 1002.21, end: 1006.81),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He describes the \"Hot Hand\" fallacy—the investor who looks at a list of funds, picks the one that went up 50% last year, and assumes it will do the same next year.", start: 1007.31, end: 1017.03),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Graham warns that \"past performance is not a guarantee of future results\" isn't just a legal disclaimer; it is an iron law.", start: 1017.49, end: 1025.55),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He observed that funds with spectacular returns usually achieved them by taking spectacular risks or getting lucky in a specific sector.", start: 1026.15, end: 1034.47),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Once that sector cools off, the \"genius\" manager looks like a fool, and the investor who bought in at the top suffers the crash.", start: 1035.03, end: 1042.13),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author’s solution was brutal honesty: most funds are just expensive marketing machines designed to gather assets, not to generate alpha.", start: 1042.67, end: 1050.69),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Index Revolution", start: 1051.43, end: 1052.63),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Today, the trap is even more subtle.", start: 1053.07, end: 1055.07),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We have \"Thematic ETFs\"—funds dedicated to AI, Cannabis, or Space Travel.", start: 1055.71, end: 1061.63),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "These are the modern version of the \"hot\" mutual funds Graham warned about.", start: 1062.43, end: 1066.83),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They package a compelling narrative (e.g., \"Robots are the future!\") and charge you a premium to own a basket of hype.", start: 1067.33, end: 1074.12),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The \"Wiser\" analysis, championed by Graham’s disciple John Bogle, is that you should stop looking for the needle in the haystack and just buy the haystack.", start: 1074.6, end: 1083.06),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The modern S&P 500 Index Fund allows you to fire the manager.", start: 1083.48, end: 1087.24),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Instead of paying 1.5% for a human to guess which stocks will go up, you pay 0.03% to a computer to own all the stocks.", start: 1087.72, end: 1096.6),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In a world where information is instant, the \"edge\" that active managers used to have is gone.", start: 1097.08, end: 1103.16),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "By indexing, you guarantee you will outperform 90% of professional investors simply by refusing to pay their salaries.", start: 1103.78, end: 1111.06),
                ]),
            ],
            7: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The greatest lie on Wall Street is a single number: \"EPS\" (Earnings Per Share).", start: 1117.3, end: 1122.26),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The friction is that you are trained to treat this number as a hard fact.", start: 1122.92, end: 1126.58),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When a company \"beats earnings estimates,\" the stock pops, and you feel safe.", start: 1127.16, end: 1132.12),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But in reality, \"Net Income\" is often an opinion—a flexible figure massaged by accountants to make management look good.", start: 1132.64, end: 1140.1),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Cash, on the other hand, is a fact.", start: 1140.76, end: 1142.88),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Most investors fail because they buy a company based on the headline profit number without realizing the business is actually bleeding cash to keep the lights on.", start: 1143.38, end: 1151.8),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They are buying a beautifully painted car with no engine.", start: 1152.6, end: 1155.58),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Kitchen Sink Trap", start: 1156.0, end: 1157.08),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author exposes this by taking us into the dark room of corporate accounting.", start: 1157.92, end: 1161.75),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He tells the story of the \"Big Bath\"—a trick where a new CEO arrives and immediately writes off every possible bad investment, lawsuit, and mistake in a single quarter.", start: 1162.17, end: 1171.89),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This makes the company look terrible for three months (which the CEO blames on the previous guy), but it clears the decks so that future earnings look artificially explosive.", start: 1172.39, end: 1181.27),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Graham warns us to ignore \"Pro Forma\" earnings—earnings that exclude \"bad stuff.\"", start: 1181.95, end: 1187.05),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He likens it to a man saying he saved $1,000 this month, provided you ignore the $5,000 he spent on gambling because that was a \"one-time event.\"", start: 1187.85, end: 1196.55),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author’s solution is to distrust the Income Statement and focus on the Balance Sheet and the dividend record.", start: 1197.65, end: 1203.57),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If a company says it is making millions but isn't paying dividends or building up cash, the author asks: \"Where is the money?\"", start: 1204.35, end: 1211.97),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The EBITDA Alibi", start: 1212.69, end: 1214.23),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In the modern era, this manipulation has evolved into \"Adjusted EBITDA\" (Earnings Before Interest, Taxes, Depreciation, and Amortization).", start: 1215.07, end: 1224.47),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This is a metric often used by high-growth Tech and AI companies to pretend they are profitable when they are not.", start: 1225.09, end: 1231.59),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Consider the WeWork debacle, where the company used \"Community Adjusted EBITDA\" to hide massive losses.", start: 1232.21, end: 1239.11),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Or look at modern software companies that pay their employees in millions of dollars of Stock-Based Compensation (SBC).", start: 1240.03, end: 1247.14),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They claim to be \"profitable\" on an adjusted basis because they treat that stock issuance as free money.", start: 1248.12, end: 1254.26),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But it isn't free—it dilutes you.", start: 1254.82, end: 1257.16),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It slices the pizza into more pieces, making your slice smaller.", start: 1257.7, end: 1261.64),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you only look at the \"Non-GAAP\" earnings promoted in the press release, you are being legally lied to.", start: 1262.24, end: 1267.9),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Protocol", start: 1268.38, end: 1270.16),
                ]),
            ],
            8: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Vacuum Trap", start: 1293.9, end: 1294.88),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The biggest mistake you make is falling in love with a stock in isolation.", start: 1295.54, end: 1299.4),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You see a company—let's say a popular coffee chain—and you think, \"I love their coffee, the line is always out the door, this must be a great investment.\"", start: 1300.26, end: 1308.82),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You buy it because the story feels good.", start: 1309.4, end: 1311.56),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This is the \"Vacuum Trap.\"", start: 1312.48, end: 1313.96),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You are judging an asset without a benchmark.", start: 1314.5, end: 1317.0),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It is like buying a house for $1 million without checking if the identical house next door just sold for $500,000.", start: 1317.36, end: 1323.0),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Friction arises because you are judging the quality of the product rather than the value of the business.", start: 1324.52, end: 1329.76),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "A great company can be a terrible investment if you pay the wrong price.", start: 1330.3, end: 1334.38),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Tale of Two Companies", start: 1334.82, end: 1336.48),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author shatters this illusion by playing a game of \"Spot the Difference.\"", start: 1336.9, end: 1340.59),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He takes two companies in the same industry—often a popular \"glamour\" stock and an unloved \"boring\" stock—and places their financials side-by-side, stripping away their names.", start: 1341.43, end: 1351.59),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He tells the story of Company A (the darling) which trades at 40 times its earnings, and Company B (the outcast) which trades at 10 times its earnings.", start: 1352.25, end: 1361.53),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Company A has a great story, but its balance sheet is loaded with debt.", start: 1362.11, end: 1365.81),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Company B is boring, but it has zero debt and twice the cash reserves.", start: 1366.33, end: 1371.23),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author reveals that to justify its price, Company A would have to grow at a miraculous rate for a decade, while Company B just has to stay alive to make you money.", start: 1371.71, end: 1381.33),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "By forcing a head-to-head comparison, the \"obvious\" choice often flips.", start: 1382.15, end: 1386.29),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The glamour stock is revealed as a speculation; the boring stock is revealed as the investment.", start: 1386.91, end: 1392.65),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The \"Tesla\" Premium", start: 1393.17, end: 1394.81),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In the modern era, this disparity has exploded.", start: 1395.35, end: 1398.05),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We see it in the \"Magnificent Seven\" versus the rest of the market.", start: 1398.53, end: 1402.03),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You might look at a high-flying EV maker or an AI chip designer trading at 80x earnings and think it's the only game in town.", start: 1402.65, end: 1410.11),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But if you run the \"Comparison Test\" against a legacy competitor—say, a boring semiconductor firm or an established auto manufacturer—you often find that the \"old\" company has higher profit margins, better dividends, and a valuation that is 80% cheaper.", start: 1410.75, end: 1426.55),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The modern market pays a massive premium for \"narrative.\"", start: 1427.05, end: 1430.03),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It overvalues the disruptor and undervalues the incumbent.", start: 1430.47, end: 1433.69),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Wiser Analysis isn't that you should never buy the growth stock; it’s that you must quantify exactly how much \"optimism\" you are paying for.", start: 1434.33, end: 1442.68),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you are paying 5x more for a dollar of earnings from Company X than from Company Y, you better be certain Company X is five times better.", start: 1443.38, end: 1452.46),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Usually, it isn't.", start: 1453.22, end: 1454.34),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Protocol", start: 1454.8, end: 1455.5),
                ]),
            ],
            9: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Junk Food Portfolio", start: 1491.7, end: 1492.94),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Most investors suffer from financial obesity.", start: 1493.54, end: 1496.42),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You fill your portfolio with \"empty calories\"—companies that have great stories but zero nutritional value.", start: 1497.18, end: 1503.52),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You buy the hot EV startup that hasn't sold a car, or the biotech firm with no revenue, because you are hungry for growth.", start: 1504.14, end: 1511.1),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The friction is that in a bull market, junk rises just like quality.", start: 1511.84, end: 1515.78),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You feel smart holding these fragile companies.", start: 1516.4, end: 1518.76),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But when the market turns, the junk crashes 90% and never recovers, while the quality stocks just go on a diet.", start: 1519.4, end: 1526.0),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You fail because you have no standards; you let any stock into your house just because it knocked on the door.", start: 1526.74, end: 1532.53),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Seven-Point Bouncer", start: 1533.09, end: 1534.79),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author solves this by hiring a ruthless bouncer for your portfolio.", start: 1535.27, end: 1538.99),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He creates a specific \"Defensive Screen\"—a checklist of seven strict requirements that a company must meet before you even consider buying it.", start: 1539.75, end: 1547.91),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author tells us that a Defensive Investor is not a talent scout looking for the next big thing; he is a quality control inspector.", start: 1548.35, end: 1556.23),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He demands:", start: 1556.65, end: 1557.27),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Adequate Size: No small, risky companies.", start: 1557.79, end: 1560.79),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Strong Financials: Current assets must be at least twice current liabilities.", start: 1561.39, end: 1566.11),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Earnings Stability: Positive earnings for the last 10 years.", start: 1566.77, end: 1570.47),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "No losses allowed.", start: 1570.97, end: 1572.11),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Dividend Record: Uninterrupted payments for 20 years.", start: 1572.65, end: 1575.61),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Earnings Growth: A minimum increase of 33% over the last 10 years.", start: 1576.11, end: 1581.37),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Moderate P/E: The price should not be more than 15 times average earnings.", start: 1581.81, end: 1586.11),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Moderate Price-to-Book: The price should not be more than 1.5 times the book value.", start: 1586.65, end: 1591.93),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If a stock fails even one of these tests, the bouncer throws it out.", start: 1592.41, end: 1596.27),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It doesn't matter if it's the \"future of technology\"; if it doesn't have the numbers, it doesn't get in.", start: 1596.85, end: 1602.07),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Zombie Apocalypse", start: 1602.61, end: 1603.99),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In the modern era, this screen is your only defense against \"Zombie Companies\"—firms that don't earn enough profit to cover the interest on their debt.", start: 1604.51, end: 1611.93),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In the last decade of near-zero interest rates, thousands of these zombies have survived by borrowing cheap money.", start: 1612.43, end: 1618.92),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They are the SPACs, the unprofitable tech IPOs, and the \"disruptors\" that bleed cash.", start: 1619.54, end: 1625.12),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You can apply Graham’s screen to filter out the noise of the modern tech bubble.", start: 1625.7, end: 1630.18),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "While you might relax the P/E ratio slightly for high-quality tech giants (who have asset-light models), the core principle remains: Profits matter.", start: 1630.62, end: 1639.4),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Dividends matter.", start: 1640.0, end: 1641.02),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "A company like Uber or Airbnb in their early years would have been rejected by this screen—and Graham would be fine with that.", start: 1641.64, end: 1648.16),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He would rather miss a Google than suffer a WeWork.", start: 1648.6, end: 1651.32),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Today, you can automate this by looking at \"Dividend Aristocrats\" or \"Quality Factor\" ETFs, which effectively run this code for you.", start: 1651.76, end: 1659.98),
                ]),
            ],
            10: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Dumpster Diver's Dilemma", start: 1668.06, end: 1669.46),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "To be an Enterprising Investor, you must be willing to do something that feels physically repulsive: you must buy what others are throwing away.", start: 1670.06, end: 1677.7),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The friction here is intense social pressure.", start: 1678.64, end: 1680.86),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When a company is failing, the headlines are screaming \"Bankruptcy!\" and your friends are laughing at it.", start: 1681.34, end: 1686.4),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "To buy it then requires a stomach of steel.", start: 1686.86, end: 1689.2),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Most people fail at this because they crave the safety of the herd.", start: 1689.68, end: 1693.22),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They want to buy \"good\" companies that are winning.", start: 1693.78, end: 1697.08),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But the Enterprising Investor knows a secret: a \"bad\" company at a dirt-cheap price is a better investment than a \"good\" company at an exorbitant price.", start: 1697.56, end: 1706.34),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You aren't looking for quality; you are looking for a mispricing so severe that the market is practically handing you free money.", start: 1706.82, end: 1713.11),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Cigar Butt Strategy", start: 1713.79, end: 1715.01),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author famously formalized this with the concept of the \"Net-Net.\"", start: 1715.55, end: 1719.75),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He tells the story of a specific type of bargain that was once common: a company trading for less than its liquidation value.", start: 1720.31, end: 1727.09),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Imagine a company that has $10 million in cash and inventory, owes $2 million in debt, and has a market cap of only $5 million.", start: 1727.63, end: 1735.55),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Even if the business shuts down tomorrow, sells the inventory, and pays off the debt, there is $8 million left.", start: 1736.15, end: 1742.05),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you buy the whole company for $5 million, you make an instant $3 million profit.", start: 1742.73, end: 1747.07),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This is the \"Cigar Butt\" approach.", start: 1747.65, end: 1749.23),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You find a discarded cigar on the street that is soggy and gross, but it has one good puff left in it.", start: 1749.85, end: 1755.07),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It’s free, so that puff is pure profit.", start: 1755.63, end: 1758.27),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author’s solution for the Enterprising Investor is to hunt for these statistical anomalies—companies worth more dead than alive—and buy a basket of them.", start: 1759.01, end: 1767.41),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You don't care about their future; you care that you bought a dollar bill for 50 cents.", start: 1768.13, end: 1772.25),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Hidden Assets of the Digital Age", start: 1772.81, end: 1775.15),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In the modern market, true \"Net-Nets\" are rare because computers find them instantly.", start: 1775.67, end: 1780.47),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "However, the principle remains the most powerful tool in deep value investing.", start: 1781.15, end: 1785.71),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Today, the \"hidden assets\" aren't factories or piles of coal; they are intellectual property, user bases, or even Bitcoin treasuries.", start: 1786.51, end: 1796.13),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Consider a legacy tech company that everyone thinks is a dinosaur.", start: 1796.85, end: 1800.63),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The stock is crushed.", start: 1801.15, end: 1802.57),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But on its balance sheet, it owns a massive portfolio of patents or a stake in a hot AI startup that the market has forgotten about.", start: 1802.95, end: 1810.46),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Or consider a retail chain that owns its own real estate.", start: 1810.92, end: 1814.54),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The market values the business at zero because \"retail is dead,\" but the land under the stores is worth more than the stock price.", start: 1814.98, end: 1822.2),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This is the modern \"sum-of-the-parts\" trade.", start: 1822.68, end: 1825.12),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You are looking for \"Special Situations\" where the market is so focused on the dying business that it ignores the valuable assets locked inside.", start: 1825.96, end: 1833.92),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Protocol", start: 1834.48, end: 1835.24),
                ]),
            ],
            11: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Optimism Blindfold", start: 1860.46, end: 1862.3),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The most dangerous defect in the human brain is the ability to ignore data that contradicts a happy story.", start: 1862.9, end: 1868.92),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You buy a stock because the CEO is charismatic and the vision is \"world-changing.\"", start: 1869.58, end: 1874.24),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When the footnotes in the financial report show massive debt or insider selling, you gloss over them.", start: 1874.88, end: 1879.96),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "\"They're just investing for growth,\" you tell yourself.", start: 1880.48, end: 1883.08),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The friction is that you are analyzing the narrative, not the structure.", start: 1883.64, end: 1887.04),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You are admiring the paint job on a house while termites are eating the foundation.", start: 1887.72, end: 1891.52),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "By the time the floor collapses, it is too late.", start: 1892.04, end: 1894.74),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Conglomerate House of Cards", start: 1895.28, end: 1897.34),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author masterfully exposes this by taking us back to the \"Conglomerate Boom.\"", start: 1897.88, end: 1902.05),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He tells the story of companies that stopped inventing products and started inventing accounting tricks.", start: 1902.49, end: 1907.53),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Imagine a boring company that decides to become \"exciting\" by buying up random businesses—a steel mill, an airline, a rental car agency.", start: 1907.93, end: 1917.69),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "On paper, their revenue explodes.", start: 1918.37, end: 1920.53),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The CEO looks like a genius.", start: 1920.97, end: 1922.61),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But the author peels back the curtain to reveal the rot: they paid for these acquisitions with overpriced stock and massive debt.", start: 1923.31, end: 1930.97),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The \"growth\" was an illusion created by merging sloppy businesses together.", start: 1931.85, end: 1936.15),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The \"Synergy\" they promised never happened.", start: 1936.75, end: 1939.63),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When the economy slowed down, the debt remained, but the cash flow vanished.", start: 1940.13, end: 1943.85),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The stock, once a darling of Wall Street, went to zero.", start: 1944.27, end: 1947.37),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The lesson?", start: 1947.77, end: 1948.25),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Complexity is often a mask for fraud.", start: 1948.63, end: 1951.27),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you cannot understand how a company makes money in two sentences, it probably doesn't.", start: 1951.79, end: 1956.55),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The \"Community Adjusted\" Reality", start: 1956.91, end: 1958.79),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Today, the red flags are hidden in plain sight under the guise of \"Innovation.\"", start: 1959.27, end: 1963.79),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The modern equivalent of the Conglomerate trick is the \"Pivot.\"", start: 1964.37, end: 1967.99),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When a crypto exchange collapses, or an \"AI\" startup implodes, the signs were always there.", start: 1968.59, end: 1973.81),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Consider the recent \"SPAC\" (Special Purpose Acquisition Company) mania.", start: 1974.23, end: 1978.91),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Companies with zero revenue were taken public based on PowerPoint slides projecting trillions in future profit.", start: 1979.79, end: 1985.91),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Or look at the \"WeWork\" disaster, where the company invented a metric called \"Community Adjusted EBITDA\" to pretend that renting desks at a loss was actually profitable.", start: 1986.47, end: 1996.48),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They removed the \"bad\" costs (like rent and marketing) to show a \"good\" number.", start: 1997.2, end: 2001.28),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This is not accounting; it is fiction.", start: 2001.94, end: 2004.3),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If a company pivots its entire business model to the latest buzzword (like adding \"Blockchain\" in 2017 or \"AI\" in 2024) without a working product, run.", start: 2004.94, end: 2015.48),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They are selling you stock, not software.", start: 2016.04, end: 2018.1),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Protocol", start: 2018.74, end: 2019.5),
                ]),
            ],
            12: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Perfectionist's Fallacy", start: 2038.84, end: 2040.56),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The biggest lie you tell yourself is that you can predict the future.", start: 2041.24, end: 2044.88),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You build complex spreadsheets projecting revenue for the next ten years.", start: 2045.42, end: 2049.28),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You tell yourself, \"If they grow at 15% and margins stay at 20%, the stock is worth exactly $142.50.\"", start: 2049.8, end: 2055.78),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The friction here is arrogance.", start: 2057.56, end: 2060.26),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The world is chaotic.", start: 2060.76, end: 2062.28),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Pandemics happen.", start: 2062.86, end: 2063.9),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Wars start.", start: 2064.4, end: 2065.3),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "CEOs get fired.", start: 2065.72, end: 2067.1),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If your investment only works when everything goes perfectly, you are not investing; you are walking a tightrope without a net.", start: 2067.66, end: 2074.58),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "One gust of wind, and you are dead.", start: 2075.1, end: 2077.2),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Most people fail because they pay a price that demands perfection.", start: 2077.58, end: 2081.3),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Engineering Secret", start: 2081.92, end: 2083.2),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author boils down the secret of investment success into three words: Margin of Safety.", start: 2083.7, end: 2089.05),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "To explain it, he leaves the world of finance and enters the world of engineering.", start: 2089.81, end: 2093.77),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He tells the story of building a bridge.", start: 2094.19, end: 2096.21),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you need a bridge to support a 10,000-pound truck, do you build it to hold exactly 10,000 pounds?", start: 2097.03, end: 2104.07),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "No.", start: 2104.77, end: 2104.87),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If the truck is slightly heavier or the steel is slightly weaker, the bridge collapses.", start: 2105.57, end: 2110.13),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You build it to hold 30,000 pounds.", start: 2110.63, end: 2112.99),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "That extra 20,000 pounds of capacity is your \"Margin of Safety.\"", start: 2113.51, end: 2117.87),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It is the buffer that allows for rust, bad weather, and human error.", start: 2118.39, end: 2122.27),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In investing, this means if you calculate a business is worth $100 a share (its \"intrinsic value\"), you do not pay $100.", start: 2122.77, end: 2130.43),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You pay $60.", start: 2131.89, end: 2132.27),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "That $40 gap is your protection.", start: 2133.61, end: 2135.55),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It means the company can have a bad year, the economy can tank, or your math can be wrong, and you still won't lose money.", start: 2136.01, end: 2142.97),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If things go right, you make a fortune.", start: 2143.65, end: 2145.63),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If things go wrong, you break even.", start: 2146.17, end: 2148.19),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You win by refusing to pay full price for value.", start: 2148.81, end: 2151.91),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Buffer Against Chaos", start: 2152.39, end: 2153.89),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In the modern world, this concept is the only thing standing between you and total ruin.", start: 2154.43, end: 2159.29),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We live in an era of \"Black Swans\"—unpredictable events like COVID-19 or the 2008 Financial Crisis that shatter standard economic models.", start: 2159.83, end: 2169.71),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Consider the investors who bought \"safe\" tech stocks at 100 times earnings in 2021 because \"rates will stay low forever.\"", start: 2170.19, end: 2177.79),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They had zero Margin of Safety.", start: 2178.51, end: 2180.15),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When rates rose, their portfolios fell 70%.", start: 2180.75, end: 2182.93),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Contrast this with the investor who bought energy stocks when oil was negative in 2020.", start: 2184.35, end: 2188.79),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They bought assets for pennies on the dollar.", start: 2190.23, end: 2192.21),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Even if the transition to green energy happens faster than expected, they bought so cheaply that they can't lose.", start: 2193.0, end: 2199.0),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In a world of algorithms and AI trading, the Margin of Safety is your humility.", start: 2199.66, end: 2204.66),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It is the admission that you don't know what will happen next, so you demand a discount to compensate for your ignorance.", start: 2205.22, end: 2211.2),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Protocol", start: 2211.58, end: 2212.18),
                ]),
            ],
        ],
        3: [
            1: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Have you ever noticed how the smartest people in the room often make the most disastrous financial decisions?", start: 8.26, end: 13.14),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The friction comes from a fundamental misunderstanding: we treat finance like it is physics.", start: 13.86, end: 18.4),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We believe it operates on immutable laws, formulas, and perfectly rational answers.", start: 19.02, end: 23.52),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We assume that if we just build a complex enough system—perhaps engineering intricate data architecture to process market trends and chart the future—we can perfectly conquer the market.", start: 24.22, end: 33.68),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But human beings aren't code.", start: 34.58, end: 36.0),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We fail because we optimize for a spreadsheet instead of optimizing for a peaceful night's sleep.", start: 36.56, end: 41.12),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When you design a flawless financial plan on a quiet Sunday afternoon, you are acting rationally.", start: 41.94, end: 46.64),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When the market drops 15% on a Tuesday morning and your heart starts pounding, rationality evaporates.", start: 47.18, end: 52.18),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The perfectly calculated plan shatters against the reality of human emotion.", start: 52.74, end: 56.18),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The secret the industry tries to hide is that trying to be completely, coldly rational is actually a trap.", start: 56.96, end: 61.95),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Fever of the Era", start: 63.35, end: 64.33),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author tells a compelling story about how our personal history dictates our financial reality.", start: 65.41, end: 69.73),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Imagine two different people.", start: 70.43, end: 71.65),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "One was born in 1950 and watched the stock market go essentially nowhere during their formative years in the 1970s.", start: 72.37, end: 77.67),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The other was born in 1970 and came of age during the unstoppable roaring bull market of the 1990s.", start: 78.29, end: 83.49),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you ask both of them about risk, you will get two entirely opposite answers.", start: 84.85, end: 89.07),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "And the fascinating part?", start: 89.69, end: 90.63),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "No one is crazy.", start: 91.13, end: 91.95),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author points out that every financial decision makes perfect sense to the person making it at that exact moment, heavily filtered through the tiny sliver of economic history they personally experienced.", start: 92.81, end: 102.51),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We are all viewing money through a highly distorted, individualized lens.", start: 103.09, end: 106.39),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Because our lenses are so biased, the author argues that aiming for strict rationality is a vulnerability.", start: 107.35, end: 112.69),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "A purely rational investor might look at historical data and decide to leverage themselves to the absolute limit because the expected return is mathematically positive.", start: 113.43, end: 121.33),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But a reasonable investor knows that if a sudden dip causes a margin call, or simply triggers enough anxiety to force a panic exit, the math is entirely useless.", start: 121.89, end: 129.87),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You must aim for a strategy that is reasonable enough to let you stay in the game long-term, even if it isn't flawlessly rational on paper.", start: 130.59, end: 136.71),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Trading the Algorithm for the Human", start: 137.57, end: 139.07),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Let’s drag this into the reality of right now.", start: 139.99, end: 141.97),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We are living in an era of overwhelming technological acceleration.", start: 142.51, end: 145.51),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "AI infrastructure is booming, data centers are eating massive amounts of capital, and markets swing wildly based on geopolitical murmurs or the sudden movement of a single crypto whale.", start: 146.01, end: 154.19),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Today, you hold an unprecedented amount of analytical power right in your pocket.", start: 154.59, end: 159.39),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You can deploy an autonomous Deep Research Agent to parse a decade of dense 10-K filings in minutes, and it might tell you exactly what you need to know about a company.", start: 160.15, end: 168.31),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The AI feels no fear.", start: 169.11, end: 170.39),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It doesn't sweat.", start: 170.91, end: 171.61),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It only sees pure expected value and cold, hard rationality.", start: 172.2, end: 175.72),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But you are the one who has to stare at the screen when a sudden supply chain shock causes those exact companies to plummet 20% in a week.", start: 176.58, end: 184.16),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When you look at your phone and see those red numbers flashing across your live widget, the psychological pain immediately overrides the AI's logical blueprint.", start: 185.22, end: 192.74),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In today's world of frictionless, hyper-fast mobile finance, the ultimate edge isn't just having the most sophisticated data or the fastest alert system.", start: 193.6, end: 201.78),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It is building a strategy that actively accommodates your own human flaws.", start: 202.28, end: 205.98),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If maintaining a theoretically \"perfect\" portfolio keeps you staring at the ceiling at 2 AM, it is a catastrophic strategy for you.", start: 206.86, end: 213.34),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Wealth isn't built by the person with the smartest data; it is built by the person who creates a framework reasonable enough to survive their own worst impulses.", start: 214.14, end: 221.74),
                ]),
            ],
            2: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Listen closely.", start: 234.32, end: 234.92),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The financial world is obsessed with the myth of the self-made visionary.", start: 235.66, end: 239.28),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When we see someone accumulate massive wealth, our immediate instinct is to dissect their morning routine, their work ethic, and their precise execution.", start: 239.96, end: 247.48),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We assume their success is a direct, one-to-one output of their intelligence.", start: 248.08, end: 252.02),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Conversely, when we fail, we beat ourselves up, assuming we just weren't smart enough or didn't grind hard enough.", start: 252.6, end: 258.12),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This is the friction that breaks most investors.", start: 258.88, end: 261.08),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We completely ignore the massive, invisible forces constantly acting upon our lives and our portfolios.", start: 261.68, end: 267.04),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We look at the winners and try to perfectly replicate their exact steps, completely forgetting that it is impossible to replicate their exact circumstances.", start: 267.64, end: 274.94),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When you believe you are in complete control of the outcome, every loss destroys your confidence, and every win inflates your ego to dangerous levels.", start: 275.66, end: 283.06),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Tragic Flip of the Coin", start: 283.9, end: 285.32),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author illustrates this profound truth with the story of Bill Gates and his high school friend, Kent Evans.", start: 286.28, end: 291.16),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In 1968, Bill Gates attended Lakeside School, which happened to be one of the only high schools in the entire world with access to a computer.", start: 291.82, end: 298.68),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The odds of a teenager having access to that kind of computing power at that time were roughly one in a million.", start: 299.3, end: 304.38),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "That extraordinary stroke of luck set the stage for the creation of Microsoft.", start: 305.06, end: 308.72),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But there is a darker half to this story.", start: 309.48, end: 311.06),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Gates had a best friend named Kent Evans.", start: 311.7, end: 313.62),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Kent was just as brilliant as Gates, just as obsessed with coding, and shared the exact same world-changing ambition.", start: 314.14, end: 319.6),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But before they even graduated, Kent died in a tragic mountaineering accident.", start: 320.24, end: 323.74),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The odds of a high school student dying on a mountain are also about one in a million.", start: 324.34, end: 327.68),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Gates experienced a one-in-a-million stroke of positive variance.", start: 328.16, end: 332.22),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "That is luck.", start: 332.72, end: 333.4),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Kent experienced a one-in-a-million stroke of negative variance.", start: 334.3, end: 337.8),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "That is risk.", start: 338.32, end: 339.18),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Luck and risk are siblings; they are doppelgängers.", start: 340.42, end: 343.49),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author reveals that outcomes are rarely just the result of individual effort.", start: 344.51, end: 348.37),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Furthermore, the vast majority of massive financial success is driven by \"tails\"—extreme, rare outlier events.", start: 349.23, end: 356.33),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In finance, as in business, you can be completely wrong half the time and still make a fortune, provided your few successful ventures catch a massive tailwind.", start: 357.47, end: 365.69),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You don't need to be right every time.", start: 366.77, end: 368.29),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You just need to survive long enough to catch the right wave.", start: 368.75, end: 371.45),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Catching the Algorithmic Tailwind", start: 372.79, end: 374.49),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Let's drag this into the reality of the modern market.", start: 375.81, end: 378.05),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Think about the explosive rise of AI and data center infrastructure over the last few years.", start: 379.03, end: 383.27),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Someone who heavily allocated capital into specific GPU manufacturers five years ago might be parading around as a visionary genius today.", start: 384.33, end: 391.15),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But were they truly predicting the exact trajectory of generative AI, or did they happen to be standing in the right sector right before a massive, unpredictable technological boom reshaped the global economy?", start: 392.09, end: 402.37),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you try to flawlessly replicate their specific strategy now, assuming it was pure skill, you might end up swallowing the \"risk\" side of the coin just as the market cycle shifts.", start: 403.67, end: 412.13),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In today’s hyper-connected environment—where a single regulatory shift in Clean Energy, a sudden breakthrough in decentralized networks, or an overnight geopolitical trade war can erase billions in value—you cannot accurately predict the future.", start: 413.27, end: 425.87),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The variables are too dense.", start: 426.75, end: 428.29),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Your objective is not to be a flawless oracle.", start: 428.75, end: 431.95),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Your objective is endurance.", start: 432.55, end: 434.53),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You must construct a system robust enough to weather the 99 terrible or mediocre days so that your capital is still sitting at the table when that 1 extraordinary day of massive returns finally arrives.", start: 435.19, end: 447.31),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The secret isn't predicting the tails; it's surviving the wait.", start: 448.09, end: 451.71),
                ]),
            ],
            3: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Have you ever noticed that hitting your financial targets rarely feels as good as you thought it would?", start: 459.87, end: 464.19),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You hustle, you scrape, you finally hit that magic number in your portfolio—and within forty-eight hours, the satisfaction evaporates.", start: 464.81, end: 472.35),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You immediately set a new, higher target.", start: 472.85, end: 474.99),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The friction here is that most people believe wealth is a numbers game, but it is actually a psychology game.", start: 475.77, end: 481.33),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We fail at this because we allow our ego to scale linearly with our net worth.", start: 481.97, end: 485.75),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We step onto a hedonic treadmill, convinced that if we just get a little bit more, we will finally arrive.", start: 486.39, end: 491.85),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But the goalpost has wheels.", start: 492.31, end: 493.55),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "People destroy perfectly good financial plans, taking catastrophic risks, simply because they are playing a game of comparison they can never win.", start: 494.25, end: 501.51),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Phantom in the Ferrari", start: 502.37, end: 503.55),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author crystalizes this trap through a brilliant concept called the \"Man in the Car Paradox.\"", start: 504.41, end: 508.88),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Imagine you are walking down the street and a sleek, roaring $200,000 Ferrari pulls up to the stoplight.", start: 509.62, end: 514.82),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "What goes through your mind?", start: 515.48, end: 516.42),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You almost never look at the driver and think, \"Wow, the guy driving that car is incredibly cool and successful.", start: 516.88, end: 522.02),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "I admire him.\"", start: 522.36, end: 522.92),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Instead, you look at the car and think, \"If I had that car, people would think I am cool.\"", start: 523.46, end: 527.7),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Do you see the tragic irony?", start: 528.24, end: 529.76),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The driver purchased the Ferrari explicitly to signal their wealth and command your admiration.", start: 530.34, end: 534.82),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But you bypass the driver entirely, using their expensive possession as a mirror to reflect your own desires for status.", start: 535.28, end: 541.12),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Nobody is as impressed with your stuff as you are.", start: 541.78, end: 543.86),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author also notes the tragic trajectory of incredibly wealthy executives—people who already had hundreds of millions of dollars—who committed financial crimes just to get a little bit more.", start: 544.6, end: 553.94),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They risked something they had and needed (their freedom and reputation) for something they didn't have and didn't need (a higher ranking on a billionaire's list).", start: 554.58, end: 561.86),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They completely forgot how to define the word \"enough.\"", start: 562.4, end: 564.96),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Flexing in the Digital Colosseum", start: 567.86, end: 569.48),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Let's pull this into the hyper-connected reality of today.", start: 571.2, end: 573.76),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The \"Man in the Car\" is no longer just a guy at a stoplight; he is everywhere.", start: 574.26, end: 578.1),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The ego trap has gone digital, frictionless, and infinite.", start: 578.54, end: 581.28),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Fifteen years ago, you only had to compare your financial success to your immediate neighbors.", start: 582.36, end: 586.16),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Today, because of social media, remote work digital nomads, and viral trading communities, you are forced to compare your portfolio to the top 0.001% of the global internet.", start: 586.64, end: 595.3),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You might execute a brilliant, disciplined strategy, securing a solid, sustainable return on a clean energy ETF or a well-researched AI infrastructure play.", start: 595.9, end: 603.36),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You should be thrilled.", start: 603.8, end: 604.52),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But then you open your phone and see a 19-year-old who turned a stimulus check into millions by gambling on a decentralized crypto token.", start: 604.96, end: 610.67),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Instantly, your very reasonable success feels like a failure.", start: 613.51, end: 617.63),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Your ego screams that you are falling behind.", start: 618.25, end: 620.69),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In the modern market, the ultimate scarcity isn't capital or data; it is the psychological armor required to ignore what everyone else is doing.", start: 621.45, end: 630.11),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you let the viral screenshots of overnight tech millionaires dictate your baseline for success, you will eventually take uncharacteristic risks that blow up your entire life's work.", start: 630.95, end: 640.75),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You have to realize that comparing your behind-the-scenes reality to someone else's curated highlight reel is a rigged game.", start: 641.45, end: 647.59),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The only way to win is to refuse to play.", start: 648.11, end: 650.57),
                ]),
            ],
            4: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Curse of the Maximum Yield", start: 663.85, end: 665.41),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Here is a secret that the loudest voices in the financial media desperately want you to ignore: hunting for the highest possible return is usually what destroys your wealth.", start: 666.77, end: 675.61),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The friction here is rooted in our impatience.", start: 676.65, end: 678.85),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We treat investing like a drag race, constantly scanning the horizon for the fastest-moving vehicle.", start: 679.43, end: 684.21),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If one asset is up 20% and ours is only up 8%, we feel like we are losing.", start: 684.89, end: 689.67),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "So, we switch lanes.", start: 690.15, end: 691.03),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We pivot.", start: 691.27, end: 691.73),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We interrupt the process.", start: 692.07, end: 693.29),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But wealth creation isn't a drag race; it is a glacier.", start: 694.45, end: 697.23),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Most people fail because they misunderstand the fundamental math of compounding.", start: 698.21, end: 701.79),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They think compounding is about earning massive percentages every single year.", start: 702.53, end: 706.01),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It isn't.", start: 706.47, end: 706.91),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Compounding is a stubborn, slow-moving machine that only requires one input to work its magic: unbroken, continuous time.", start: 707.61, end: 715.32),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Every time you panic, chase a new trend, or try to dodge a market dip, you unplug the machine and reset the clock to zero.", start: 716.28, end: 722.72),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The $81 Billion Birthday and the Price of Admission", start: 724.18, end: 727.04),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author shatters this illusion by pointing to the most famous investor alive: Warren Buffett.", start: 728.26, end: 733.02),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We attribute Buffett’s fortune to supreme stock-picking intelligence.", start: 733.98, end: 737.12),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But the author reveals a staggering mathematical reality: of Buffett's roughly $84.5 billion net worth (at the time the book was written), $81.5 billion of it came after his 65th birthday.", start: 737.58, end: 749.12),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Buffett isn't the greatest investor of all time because he had the highest annual returns.", start: 750.38, end: 754.22),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In fact, there are quantitative fund managers who boast significantly higher average annual returns than him.", start: 754.66, end: 759.28),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Buffett's secret is simply that he has been achieving good returns uninterrupted for three-quarters of a century.", start: 760.14, end: 765.16),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He never stopped the engine.", start: 765.74, end: 767.06),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But how do you keep the engine running when the market collapses?", start: 767.48, end: 770.36),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author explains this through the metaphor of a \"fee versus a fine.\"", start: 770.98, end: 774.4),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When you get a speeding ticket, that is a fine.", start: 775.1, end: 777.18),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It means you did something wrong; you are being punished and you should change your behavior.", start: 777.72, end: 781.64),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But when you pay $150 to get into Disneyland, that is a fee.", start: 782.4, end: 785.92),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It is simply the price of admission to experience something great.", start: 786.68, end: 789.72),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Market volatility—the agonizing 20% or 30% drops—is not a fine.", start: 790.72, end: 795.5),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It does not mean you made a mistake.", start: 796.14, end: 797.5),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It is the unavoidable fee you must pay to access the theme park of long-term compounding.", start: 798.18, end: 802.92),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Weathering the AI Super-Cycle", start: 804.22, end: 805.9),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Let’s contextualize this for the modern market.", start: 807.2, end: 809.24),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We are currently watching a massive structural shift regarding artificial intelligence, autonomous networks, and global data center expansion.", start: 809.98, end: 816.64),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The long-term trajectory of these technologies is incredibly profound.", start: 817.48, end: 820.89),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "However, the day-to-day reality of participating in this super-cycle is brutal.", start: 822.23, end: 826.09),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "A sudden semiconductor export restriction, a minor trade war whisper, or an unexpected shift in remote-work enterprise spending can send a perfectly healthy AI infrastructure company plummeting 35% in a single month.", start: 826.79, end: 839.19),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When modern investors see that flash crash on their screens, their instinct is to view it as a speeding ticket.", start: 840.45, end: 845.03),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They think, “I made a mistake, I need to exit immediately to stop the pain.”", start: 845.61, end: 848.93),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But if you truly understand the underlying thesis of the asset, that 35% drop is just the admission fee.", start: 850.21, end: 856.39),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you refuse to pay the fee of modern market volatility, you will never be allowed to stay on the ride long enough to let the compounding engine do its actual work.", start: 857.43, end: 864.83),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You cannot get a multi-decade technological tailwind for free.", start: 865.49, end: 868.51),
                ]),
            ],
            5: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Getting wealthy is glamorous; staying wealthy is agonizingly dull.", start: 874.51, end: 878.15),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The financial world glorifies the ascent.", start: 878.81, end: 880.79),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We obsess over the visionaries who see what no one else sees, the risk-takers who put everything on the line, and the bold optimists who look at a skeptical market and confidently declare, \"I am right, and everyone else is wrong.\"", start: 881.23, end: 892.77),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Getting money absolutely demands this aggressive, forward-leaning posture.", start: 893.47, end: 896.91),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You must be optimistic enough to believe that the future will be larger and more profitable than the past.", start: 897.45, end: 902.41),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But here is the brutal friction that shatters most portfolios: the very psychological traits required to make money are the exact traits that will mathematically guarantee you lose it.", start: 903.13, end: 912.37),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "People fail because they treat wealth generation and wealth preservation as the exact same discipline.", start: 913.01, end: 917.31),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They are not just different skills; they are polar opposites.", start: 917.89, end: 920.53),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "To keep your wealth, you must undergo a complete psychological inversion.", start: 921.19, end: 924.17),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You have to trade your visionary optimism for a creeping, constant paranoia.", start: 924.67, end: 928.53),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You must assume that your past success was largely a byproduct of a temporary tailwind, and that tomorrow's market is actively conspiring to take it all back.", start: 929.15, end: 936.21),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When you refuse to shift gears—when you keep your foot slammed on the accelerator of optimism after you have already won the race—you eventually drive your portfolio straight off a cliff.", start: 936.89, end: 945.21),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Ghost of Jesse Livermore and the Mechanics of Survival", start: 946.09, end: 948.73),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author illustrates this catastrophic failure to shift gears through the haunting story of Jesse Livermore.", start: 949.57, end: 954.99),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In the early 20th century, Livermore was arguably the greatest stock trader alive.", start: 955.73, end: 960.01),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When the catastrophic market crash of 1929 hit, wiping out a generation of wealth and plunging the nation into the Great Depression, Livermore’s wife locked their doors, assuming they were completely ruined like everyone else in their social circle.", start: 960.69, end: 972.43),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But Livermore returned home with unbelievable news: he had aggressively shorted the market.", start: 973.09, end: 977.71),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "While the world burned, Livermore made the modern equivalent of over three billion dollars in a single week.", start: 978.33, end: 983.27),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He had achieved the ultimate financial victory.", start: 984.27, end: 986.41),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He was invincible.", start: 986.95, end: 988.03),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But Livermore could not turn off the risk-taking engine that made him a billionaire.", start: 988.77, end: 992.11),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He kept placing massive, highly leveraged, wildly optimistic bets on the market, assuming his own genius was a permanent shield.", start: 992.65, end: 998.87),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He lacked the paranoia required to protect what he had built.", start: 999.51, end: 1001.97),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Four years later, Livermore had lost absolutely everything, culminating in tragedy.", start: 1002.79, end: 1007.27),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This story perfectly highlights the author’s concept of \"Room for Error,\" often called the margin of safety.", start: 1007.87, end: 1013.05),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Room for error is the unspoken, unglamorous secret of the world's most enduring investors.", start: 1013.9, end: 1018.78),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It is the understanding that your predictive models will eventually be wrong.", start: 1019.44, end: 1022.78),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If your financial plan requires the market to perform exactly as you predicted in order for you to survive, you are playing Russian roulette.", start: 1023.54, end: 1029.8),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Building an unbreakable defense means engineering a life and a portfolio that can endure a reality where your assumptions are completely shattered.", start: 1030.62, end: 1037.74),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It is the realization that survival is not just one of the strategies; survival is the only foundation upon which compounding can actually work.", start: 1038.46, end: 1045.68),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you are forced out of the game during a downturn, your past brilliance is entirely erased.", start: 1046.36, end: 1050.56),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Surviving the Algorithmic Meat Grinder", start: 1052.02, end: 1053.78),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Fast forward to our current reality.", start: 1055.18, end: 1056.62),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The velocity of money and the sheer speed of information have violently accelerated.", start: 1057.08, end: 1060.96),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We are navigating an era of unprecedented leverage and hyperspeed narrative-driven markets.", start: 1061.52, end: 1066.08),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Consider the billions of dollars currently flowing into AI infrastructure and massive data centers, the wild swings of clean energy ETFs reacting to a single regulatory rumor, or the chaotic, 24/7 global casino of cryptocurrency.", start: 1066.72, end: 1078.92),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In this hyper-connected environment, the illusion of safety is a dangerous and intoxicating trap.", start: 1080.2, end: 1085.0),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "People build complex, highly optimized portfolios that work flawlessly—right up until a sudden geopolitical trade war severs a critical semiconductor supply chain, or an unforeseen algorithmic shift triggers a cascading flash crash across the network.", start: 1085.64, end: 1098.12),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Today, having room for error isn't just about keeping a percentage of your portfolio in cash.", start: 1098.56, end: 1103.54),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It is about structural, psychological defense.", start: 1104.12, end: 1106.46),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It means asking yourself what happens if the remote work trend completely reverses, commercial real estate collapses, and the specific tech sector you are heavily exposed to experiences a decade-long winter.", start: 1107.2, end: 1117.9),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "A modern margin of safety means recognizing that the unprecedented will happen.", start: 1117.9, end: 1122.56),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you have leveraged yourself to the absolute maximum to capture the upside of the current AI super-cycle, you have left yourself zero room for error when the inevitable, unpredictable macro-shock arrives, that lack of a safety net will force you to liquidate your positions at the absolute worst time just to survive.", start: 1123.5, end: 1139.6),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You must be skeptical enough to build a massive financial moat today, precisely so you can afford to be optimistic about the decades to come.", start: 1140.52, end: 1147.58),
                ]),
            ],
            6: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Here is a reality most people completely misunderstand about capital: we are conditioned to view money strictly as a medium of exchange for physical goods.", start: 1162.96, end: 1171.66),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You earn money to exchange it for a car, a house, a vacation, or a watch.", start: 1172.26, end: 1176.2),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The friction that traps almost every investor is the belief that if you are not actively spending your money on something tangible, that money is sitting idle and useless.", start: 1176.9, end: 1185.02),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Because of this, people only save with a specific purchase in mind.", start: 1186.26, end: 1189.76),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They save for a down payment.", start: 1190.22, end: 1191.46),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They save for a wedding.", start: 1191.7, end: 1192.7),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But when you only view money as a ticket to acquire things, you inevitably fall victim to lifestyle creep.", start: 1193.3, end: 1198.32),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The moment your income increases, your desires stretch to match it.", start: 1199.0, end: 1202.24),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You upgrade your apartment, you upgrade your car, and suddenly your new, massive income is entirely spoken for.", start: 1202.68, end: 1208.28),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You feel wealthy because you are surrounded by expensive items, but you are actually chained to a higher burn rate.", start: 1208.88, end: 1214.02),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You are forced to work harder, take on more stress, and answer to more people just to maintain the baseline.", start: 1214.48, end: 1219.56),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You have succeeded in acquiring money, but you have failed to acquire the one thing money is actually designed to buy.", start: 1220.14, end: 1225.56),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Highest Dividend", start: 1230.06, end: 1231.1),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author shatters this consumption mindset by revealing what he considers the single greatest intrinsic value of a dollar.", start: 1234.4, end: 1240.36),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He argues that the absolute highest dividend money can possibly pay is the ability to control your own time.", start: 1240.94, end: 1246.64),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "To illustrate this, the author points to a massive, multi-decade study of elderly populations.", start: 1247.94, end: 1253.66),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When researchers asked thousands of elderly people what the secret to a happy life was, almost none of them said \"working hard to make enough money to buy things.\"", start: 1254.32, end: 1262.8),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "None of them cared about the size of their former houses or the prestige of their titles.", start: 1263.64, end: 1267.94),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The overwhelmingly common denominator for happiness was having quality time, strong relationships, and the autonomy to dictate their own schedules.", start: 1268.64, end: 1276.78),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author explains that the most powerful form of saving is saving for absolutely nothing at all.", start: 1278.46, end: 1283.42),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You do not need a specific reason to save.", start: 1284.06, end: 1286.38),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When you save without a goal, you are no longer saving to buy a product; you are saving to buy options.", start: 1286.86, end: 1292.27),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You are purchasing a hedge against life's inevitable unpredictability.", start: 1292.75, end: 1296.25),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Every unspent dollar in your bank account represents a tiny piece of your future that you own outright.", start: 1297.89, end: 1302.81),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It represents the ability to take a lower-paying job that you actually love, the ability to walk away from a toxic boss, or the ability to take a six-month sabbatical without your life falling apart.", start: 1303.45, end: 1313.95),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "True wealth is waking up in the morning and saying, \"I can do whatever I want today.\"", start: 1314.91, end: 1319.39),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Digital Sweatshop", start: 1321.03, end: 1322.13),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Let’s translate this into the hyper-accelerated modern era.", start: 1323.79, end: 1326.63),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Look around at the current boom in tech, remote work, and the frantic race to capitalize on artificial intelligence.", start: 1327.35, end: 1332.87),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We now have a generation of highly paid \"digital nomads\" and tech executives making staggering amounts of money.", start: 1333.45, end: 1340.11),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But look closely at their lives.", start: 1340.89, end: 1342.71),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "A remote worker might be pulling in $300,000 a year, but if they are terrified of being replaced by the latest generative AI model, and are chained to their Slack notifications 24/7 to prove their productivity, they are not free.", start: 1343.45, end: 1356.75),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They have a massive income, but they are living in a digital sweatshop.", start: 1357.35, end: 1360.69),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They have zero autonomy over their Tuesday afternoon.", start: 1361.25, end: 1363.71),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Conversely, consider someone who built a modest, unglamorous portfolio—perhaps a steady accumulation of basic index funds or stable tech mainstays—but purposely kept their living expenses incredibly low.", start: 1365.21, end: 1377.13),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They don't have the income to charter a private jet, but they have accumulated enough unspent capital to insulate themselves from the AI panic.", start: 1377.83, end: 1384.73),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If their industry shifts or a global pandemic reshapes the economy, they don't have to scramble.", start: 1385.41, end: 1389.83),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They have the flexibility to pause, pivot, and retrain at their own pace.", start: 1390.27, end: 1394.13),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In today's world, where algorithms can execute trades in milliseconds and remote work blurs the line between the office and the bedroom, your time is under constant siege.", start: 1395.53, end: 1404.29),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you are using your portfolio just to fund a more expensive lifestyle, you are missing his point.", start: 1404.91, end: 1409.41),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You should be using your portfolio to buy yourself out of the modern grind.", start: 1410.03, end: 1413.15),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Your wealth is measured not by what you can purchase, but by how many months you can truly \"live\" without asking anyone for permission!", start: 1413.79, end: 1420.03),
                ]),
            ],
            7: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Here is a psychological trap that almost everyone falls into: we rely on visual cues to measure success.", start: 1427.39, end: 1433.57),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you want to know if someone is physically fit, you look at them.", start: 1434.21, end: 1436.87),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you want to know if someone is a good public speaker, you listen to them.", start: 1437.39, end: 1440.13),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "So, logically, if you want to know if someone is doing well financially, you look at their lifestyle.", start: 1440.65, end: 1444.89),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You look at the car they drive, the zip code they live in, and the photos they post.", start: 1445.35, end: 1448.65),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The friction arises because this logic is entirely backwards when it comes to finance.", start: 1449.35, end: 1453.53),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The only definitive thing you know about someone driving a $100,000 car is that they have $100,000 less in the bank than they did yesterday—or worse, they are drowning in $100,000 of debt.", start: 1454.11, end: 1464.97),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "People completely fail at building long-term security because they are trying to emulate the spending patterns of the rich, completely misunderstanding that true wealth is exactly what you cannot see.", start: 1465.81, end: 1475.09),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When you use your money to signal to the world how much money you have, you are actively destroying the very thing you are trying to display.", start: 1475.89, end: 1482.11),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Price of the Unbought", start: 1484.01, end: 1485.21),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author delivers a masterclass on this distinction by brutally separating two words society uses interchangeably: \"Rich\" and \"Wealthy.\"", start: 1485.85, end: 1492.87),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Rich is a current income.", start: 1493.63, end: 1494.93),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It is highly visible.", start: 1495.29, end: 1496.21),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Even someone drowning in debt can be \"rich\" if their monthly cash flow is high enough to cover the interest payments on their massive mansion and sports car.", start: 1496.71, end: 1503.07),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Wealth, however, is hidden.", start: 1503.51, end: 1505.19),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Wealth is the income not spent.", start: 1505.91, end: 1507.75),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author tells the story of the singer Rihanna, who nearly went bankrupt and sued her financial advisor.", start: 1508.55, end: 1513.63),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The advisor’s defense was a profound, almost sarcastic truth: \"Was it really necessary to tell her that if you spend money on things, you will end up with the things and not the money?\"", start: 1514.31, end: 1524.65),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author confesses that his own personal financial strategy isn't about maximizing every single yield or driving a spectacular car.", start: 1525.89, end: 1532.99),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He and his family purposefully live a quiet, unglamorous lifestyle with a massive savings rate.", start: 1533.69, end: 1538.75),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Why?", start: 1539.21, end: 1539.45),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Because wealth is the luxury car not purchased.", start: 1540.09, end: 1542.7),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It is the big diamond ring not bought.", start: 1543.14, end: 1545.04),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It is the first-class upgrade declined.", start: 1545.56, end: 1547.44),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Wealth is financial assets that have not yet been converted into the stuff you see.", start: 1548.16, end: 1552.06),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It is a quiet, hidden ledger of options, flexibility, and unspent potential.", start: 1552.74, end: 1557.3),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you cannot embrace the agonizingly boring act of leaving money alone, you will never build wealth; you will only ever build a facade.", start: 1558.1, end: 1565.5),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Digital Flex Economy", start: 1569.16, end: 1570.48),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Let’s pull this into the hyper-visible reality of the present moment.", start: 1571.7, end: 1574.56),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The pressure to look rich has exponentially mutated.", start: 1575.08, end: 1577.74),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It is no longer just the guy in your neighborhood showing off a new lawnmower; it is a global, 24/7 digital colosseum.", start: 1578.26, end: 1584.7),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Look at the modern crypto ecosystem, or the explosive wealth narratives surrounding early AI infrastructure investments.", start: 1585.64, end: 1591.12),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Every single day, you are bombarded with screenshots of massive decentralized wallet balances, tech founders flashing their lavish remote-work setups in Bali, or traders showcasing massive overnight gains from an obscure Data Center REIT.", start: 1591.76, end: 1603.36),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This is the modern flex.", start: 1603.98, end: 1605.14),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But remember the rule of the unseen: you are only seeing the highlight reel.", start: 1605.68, end: 1609.96),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "What that viral screenshot does not show you is the crippling margin debt holding that portfolio together.", start: 1610.56, end: 1615.5),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It does not show you the catastrophic tax liability waiting at the end of the year.", start: 1616.18, end: 1619.86),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It does not show you the insomnia.", start: 1620.48, end: 1621.88),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In an era where everyone can instantly broadcast their perceived success, the desire to convert your unspent capital into visible status is overwhelming.", start: 1623.56, end: 1632.02),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you acquire a solid, life-changing return from a clean energy ETF, your ego will scream at you to immediately upgrade your lifestyle so the world knows you succeeded.", start: 1632.74, end: 1641.64),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You have to fight this modern instinct with everything you have.", start: 1642.26, end: 1645.08),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The ultimate flex in today's digital economy is having an unassailable, deeply secure financial foundation that absolutely no one on the internet knows about.", start: 1645.64, end: 1653.84),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "True wealth is silent.", start: 1654.44, end: 1655.8),
                ]),
            ],
            8: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Here is the most dangerous assumption embedded in modern finance: the belief that the past is a perfect blueprint for the future.", start: 1663.06, end: 1669.44),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We are conditioned to treat financial history like a hard science.", start: 1670.38, end: 1673.28),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We look at past recessions, past technological revolutions, and past market crashes, and we build elaborate, hyper-detailed models to predict exactly what will happen next.", start: 1673.96, end: 1682.96),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The friction that destroys so many portfolios is the misplaced confidence that if you just study enough historical data, you can eliminate uncertainty.", start: 1684.04, end: 1691.28),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But people fail because they are studying a world that no longer exists.", start: 1692.52, end: 1695.84),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They build highly rigid, decades-long financial plans assuming two things will remain absolutely static: the macroeconomic environment, and their own personal desires.", start: 1696.5, end: 1704.78),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Both of these assumptions are fatal.", start: 1705.34, end: 1706.86),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When you lock yourself into a rigid, mathematically optimized master plan, you are completely defenseless when the world inevitably does something it has never done before.", start: 1707.86, end: 1715.24),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Even worse, you are trapped when you wake up a decade later and realize the person you are today no longer wants the things the person you were ten years ago was saving for.", start: 1716.06, end: 1723.14),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Prophet’s Fallacy and the Stranger in the Mirror", start: 1724.36, end: 1726.59),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author dismantles this rigid thinking by exposing two profound psychological blind spots.", start: 1727.73, end: 1731.89),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "First, he addresses the illusion of history.", start: 1732.51, end: 1734.35),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Economic history is not a map of the future; it is a study of unprecedented, unpredictable surprises.", start: 1735.17, end: 1740.43),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Think about the most consequential economic events of the last century—the Great Depression, World War II, the dot-com bubble, or the 2008 financial crisis.", start: 1741.25, end: 1748.97),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "None of these events were historically precedented when they occurred.", start: 1749.61, end: 1752.07),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you only use history as a guide to the future, you act like a prophet who is only looking in the rearview mirror.", start: 1752.61, end: 1758.29),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You will successfully predict the previous crisis, but you will be completely blindsided by the next one, because the next crisis will look entirely different.", start: 1759.03, end: 1766.57),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author then pairs this with a brilliant concept from psychology: the \"End of History Illusion.\"", start: 1767.69, end: 1772.41),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you look back at who you were ten years ago, you will easily recognize how drastically your goals, personality, and priorities have changed.", start: 1773.31, end: 1779.91),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "However, when we look forward, we suffer from a massive failure of imagination.", start: 1780.61, end: 1784.63),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We almost always assume that who we are today is the finished product.", start: 1785.33, end: 1788.83),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We assume our current career ambitions, risk tolerance, and lifestyle desires will remain permanently fixed until we retire.", start: 1789.47, end: 1795.19),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This illusion leads to catastrophic financial rigidity.", start: 1796.37, end: 1798.83),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "A young professional might commit to an extreme, punishing frugality strategy to retire at thirty-five, only to realize at thirty-five that they actually love their work and want the capital to start a massive business instead.", start: 1799.51, end: 1809.43),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author warns that because you cannot predict the global economy, and you cannot even predict your own future personality, avoiding extreme financial commitments is the only way to survive.", start: 1810.37, end: 1819.49),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The AI Event Horizon and the Shifting Self", start: 1823.79, end: 1826.05),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Let’s translate this into the hyper-volatile reality you are navigating right now.", start: 1830.21, end: 1833.55),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Look at the explosion of generative AI, the staggering energy demands of modern Data Centers, and the sudden, decentralized architecture of Crypto.", start: 1834.13, end: 1841.29),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you try to map the current AI infrastructure super-cycle perfectly onto the 1990s internet boom, you will get crushed.", start: 1841.83, end: 1848.87),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The 1990s did not feature the same complex, interwoven geopolitical supply chains, immediate remote-work workforce distributions, or the instantaneous, algorithmic capital flight we see today.", start: 1849.49, end: 1860.75),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We are living in an era where an unexpected trade war over a tiny semiconductor component can freeze an entire global sector overnight.", start: 1861.58, end: 1868.72),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The world is writing new rules in real-time.", start: 1869.44, end: 1871.7),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "History cannot save you here.", start: 1872.48, end: 1873.9),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "More importantly, your relationship to this new economy will evolve.", start: 1874.74, end: 1877.94),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Right now, you might have a high-risk tolerance.", start: 1878.72, end: 1880.66),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You might be perfectly content concentrating your capital into volatile tech ETFs, fully willing to endure brutal 30% swings.", start: 1881.14, end: 1887.88),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But what happens in seven years if you have a family, or decide to move across the country, or suddenly discover a passion for a totally different, lower-paying industry?", start: 1888.7, end: 1896.4),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If your financial architecture is so rigid that it only works if you remain an aggressive, risk-hungry tech investor forever, you are building a prison.", start: 1897.42, end: 1904.5),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "True financial mastery in the modern era requires extreme adaptability.", start: 1905.36, end: 1909.1),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You have to build a system that leaves room for the global economy to shock you, and leaves room for you to shock yourself.", start: 1909.9, end: 1915.22),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You must refuse to become a prisoner to your own past predictions.", start: 1916.04, end: 1919.16),
                ]),
            ],
            9: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Here is the invisible trapdoor in the financial world: assuming everyone on the field is playing the exact same sport.", start: 1932.6, end: 1938.56),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Most people fail at wealth creation because they suffer from financial identity theft.", start: 1939.46, end: 1943.26),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They watch a stranger double their net worth in three weeks and immediately feel a sickening wave of FOMO.", start: 1944.04, end: 1949.1),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They assume, subconsciously, that the stranger’s victory is their own missed opportunity.", start: 1949.96, end: 1953.96),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But this is an illusion.", start: 1954.6, end: 1955.54),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The friction arises when you take a financial cue from someone who has radically different risk tolerances, goals, and time horizons than you do.", start: 1956.3, end: 1962.78),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You wouldn't watch a marathon runner sprinting the final 100 yards and decide to adopt that pace for the first mile of your own race.", start: 1963.84, end: 1969.72),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Yet, in the markets, everyday people constantly mimic the moves of institutional sprinters, completely forgetting they are supposed to be running a marathon.", start: 1970.38, end: 1977.14),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Tale of Two Bubbles", start: 1977.96, end: 1979.12),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author tells the story of the late 1990s Dot-Com bubble to illustrate this exact psychological blind spot.", start: 1979.94, end: 1985.19),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Why did otherwise rational, educated people pay utterly unjustifiable prices for internet companies with zero revenue?", start: 1985.91, end: 1991.67),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The common narrative is that people just lost their minds to greed.", start: 1992.35, end: 1994.73),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But the author argues something much more nuanced: the prices actually made perfect sense for the people setting them—the day traders.", start: 1995.25, end: 2000.99),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If a momentum trader acquires a tech stock at $60 with the sole intention of flipping it by lunchtime for $61, they don't care about cash flow, fundamentals, or a ten-year valuation.", start: 2001.73, end: 2010.11),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "For their specific, short-term game, the price is entirely rational.", start: 2010.71, end: 2013.99),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The disaster strikes when a long-term investor, looking to fund a retirement two decades away, sees the day trader's momentum and copies the move.", start: 2014.49, end: 2022.83),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The long-term investor is operating under the delusion that the short-term trader knows something they don't.", start: 2023.67, end: 2028.61),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They take their cues from someone playing a fundamentally different game, and when the bubble bursts, the long-term player is left clutching the ashes while the day trader has long since moved on.", start: 2029.39, end: 2038.99),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The AI Illusion", start: 2040.63, end: 2041.73),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Today, this trap is infinitely more dangerous because the noise is deafening.", start: 2043.37, end: 2047.33),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We no longer just have day traders; we have high-frequency trading networks, deep learning models, and massive institutional capital dictating market momentum.", start: 2048.01, end: 2056.17),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Consider the current explosion in artificial intelligence and the massive capital flowing into data centers and semiconductor infrastructure.", start: 2057.07, end: 2063.75),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When a quantitative fund deploys a complex deep learning LSTM network or uses cluster analysis to detect micro-anomalies in tech valuations, that machine is optimizing for a game measured in days, hours, or even milliseconds.", start: 2064.75, end: 2077.27),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If an everyday investor opens an interface, sees a massive price spike driven by those algorithmic maneuvers, and decides to jump in for their 30-year portfolio, they are committing the ultimate unforced error.", start: 2078.37, end: 2088.88),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They are copying the homework of an entity that is solving an entirely different equation.", start: 2089.48, end: 2093.36),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The same applies to the rapid rotations into clean energy ETFs or reacting to geopolitical trade-war rumors.", start: 2093.96, end: 2100.48),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The headlines will scream about massive daily gains or steep drops, but those headlines never disclose the time horizon of the people taking the profits or cutting their losses.", start: 2101.22, end: 2110.32),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you are building wealth for a decade from now, the daily noise of someone optimizing for tomorrow's closing bell is worse than useless to you—it is actively destructive.", start: 2111.18, end: 2120.34),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "True financial clarity comes from writing down exactly what game you are playing, and then putting blinders on.", start: 2121.08, end: 2126.52),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You have to clearly define your own financial identity and ruthlessly ignore the noise from everyone else.", start: 2127.22, end: 2132.74),
                ]),
            ],
            10: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Sit in any busy coffee shop, open up your laptop, and scroll through the day's financial headlines.", start: 2140.46, end: 2145.6),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Notice how the articles predicting a catastrophic market collapse are always written by people who sound like absolute geniuses.", start: 2146.52, end: 2152.36),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They use complex macroeconomic jargon, cite geopolitical trade wars, and weave intricate data models to prove that the sky is falling.", start: 2153.04, end: 2160.28),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In contrast, the person quietly saying, \"I think the market will probably be higher in ten years,\" sounds like a naive amateur.", start: 2161.1, end: 2167.9),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This is the friction that destroys most portfolios.", start: 2169.0, end: 2171.42),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We are biologically wired to treat pessimism as an intellectual flex.", start: 2172.12, end: 2175.44),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Evolution taught our ancestors that treating a rustle in the bushes as a deadly predator kept them alive, while assuming it was just the wind got them killed.", start: 2176.28, end: 2183.04),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In the financial world, pessimism sounds like someone desperately trying to save your life.", start: 2183.96, end: 2187.72),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Optimism sounds like a cheap, oblivious sales pitch.", start: 2188.38, end: 2190.78),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The reason most people fail at long-term wealth creation is that they let the intellectual seduction of pessimism talk them out of the mathematical reality of human progress.", start: 2191.66, end: 2199.39),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Adaptation Blindspot", start: 2200.59, end: 2201.79),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author highlights a fatal flaw in pessimistic forecasting: it assumes human beings just stand still and blindly take the punishment.", start: 2202.75, end: 2209.19),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When experts predict a crisis, they almost always draw a straight, downward line from today's problem directly into the future.", start: 2210.05, end: 2215.69),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "What they consistently fail to model is human adaptation.", start: 2216.51, end: 2220.21),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author points out the profound pessimism that follows major economic crashes or resource shortages.", start: 2220.91, end: 2226.61),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Consider the early 2000s, when the smartest people in the room mathematically \"proved\" we had reached peak oil production and global economies would soon grind to a halt.", start: 2227.39, end: 2236.11),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "What the pessimists didn't calculate was that the looming threat of running out of oil created a massive, urgent financial incentive to invent horizontal drilling and fracking.", start: 2237.07, end: 2246.27),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The problem itself funded the solution.", start: 2246.97, end: 2248.81),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Optimism isn't the delusional belief that everything will be perfect, that crashes won't happen, or that you won't lose money in the short term.", start: 2249.77, end: 2256.09),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "True financial optimism is the baseline belief that the odds of a good outcome are in your favor over time, because human beings are incredibly efficient at solving problems when their backs are against the wall.", start: 2256.81, end: 2266.97),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Pessimists extrapolate the disaster; optimists bank on the response.", start: 2267.77, end: 2271.51),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Cortisol Economy", start: 2275.31, end: 2276.47),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Today, this biological glitch is being ruthlessly exploited.", start: 2280.47, end: 2284.05),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You are not just fighting your own evolutionary wiring; you are fighting algorithms explicitly designed to monetize your anxiety.", start: 2284.63, end: 2290.79),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Consider the current narrative around the technology sector.", start: 2291.69, end: 2294.19),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "On any given day, you can find brilliantly articulated, data-backed reports explaining why the artificial intelligence infrastructure build-out is a massive, unsustainable bubble.", start: 2294.81, end: 2303.45),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You will read deeply researched white papers on how data center energy consumption will collapse the power grid, or how international trade wars will permanently sever the semiconductor supply chain.", start: 2304.51, end: 2313.46),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "These arguments sound incredibly urgent, smart, and terrifying.", start: 2313.9, end: 2318.24),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But they entirely discount the invisible army of engineers and entrepreneurs currently working 80-hour weeks to optimize GPU efficiency, pioneer next-generation cooling systems, and build resilient, localized supply chains.", start: 2318.78, end: 2333.3),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The media will amplify the looming disaster of an AI bottleneck because panic drives clicks and engagement.", start: 2334.06, end: 2339.92),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But betting on that doom means betting against thousands of incredibly smart people who are incentivized by billions of dollars to solve that exact bottleneck.", start: 2340.48, end: 2349.44),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "History shows that betting against human ingenuity is a terrible long-term strategy.", start: 2350.22, end: 2354.56),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The smart money knows that pessimism is for the headlines, but optimism is for the portfolio.", start: 2355.36, end: 2359.96),
                ]),
            ],
            11: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Look at the current state of the global market.", start: 2371.72, end: 2373.76),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We are navigating an era of unprecedented chaos—shifting interest rates, volatile geopolitical trade wars, and entire industries being upended overnight by new technologies.", start: 2374.34, end: 2384.66),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In the middle of this storm, human beings are desperate for a map.", start: 2385.42, end: 2388.66),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We crave a predictable world, one where a simple, guaranteed formula leads directly to financial freedom.", start: 2389.22, end: 2395.06),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This craving is the invisible friction that destroys so many portfolios.", start: 2395.88, end: 2399.84),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When you desperately need an outcome to be true—because you feel behind on retirement, because inflation is eating your savings, or because you just want to escape the 9-to-5 grind—your brain stops processing cold, hard data.", start: 2400.56, end: 2412.3),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Instead, it starts hunting for a comforting narrative.", start: 2412.88, end: 2415.4),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Most people fail at investing not because they lack intelligence, but because they are easily seduced by storytellers who promise them exactly what they want to hear.", start: 2416.18, end: 2424.45),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They want a predictable universe so badly that they willingly accept financial fictions.", start: 2425.13, end: 2429.57),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Hallucination of the Oasis", start: 2430.51, end: 2432.05),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author highlights a profound psychological vulnerability: the more you want something to be true, the more likely you are to overestimate the odds of it actually being true.", start: 2432.91, end: 2441.73),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Think of a wanderer lost in the desert.", start: 2442.57, end: 2444.39),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When a person is dying of thirst, they don't just hope there is a lake over the next sand dune; their brain actually fabricates a mirage.", start: 2444.95, end: 2451.53),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They hallucinate an oasis because their body desperately needs water to survive.", start: 2451.99, end: 2456.03),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The exact same psychological mechanism operates in finance.", start: 2456.49, end: 2459.47),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If a person is 55 years old, severely underfunded for retirement, and terrified of running out of money, they are wandering in a financial desert.", start: 2459.93, end: 2466.85),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When a charismatic fund manager or a loud internet guru pitches them a revolutionary new strategy guaranteeing a 20% annual return, the investor doesn't look at the math.", start: 2467.45, end: 2476.15),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They don't audit the historical failure rate of such promises.", start: 2476.55, end: 2478.89),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They look at the pitch and see an oasis.", start: 2479.35, end: 2481.19),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They believe the story because the alternative—that they have to work for ten more years and drastically cut their standard of living—is too painful to accept.", start: 2481.75, end: 2488.61),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The narrative acts as an anesthetic against reality.", start: 2489.17, end: 2491.51),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Inevitability Trap", start: 2492.19, end: 2493.19),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Today, the financial deserts are crowded, and the mirages are incredibly sophisticated.", start: 2494.25, end: 2498.33),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We see this vividly in the massive narratives surrounding the Clean Energy transition and the Electric Vehicle (EV) revolution.", start: 2498.85, end: 2504.19),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The story being aggressively pushed is that a carbon-neutral world is an absolute, inevitable certainty.", start: 2504.85, end: 2509.53),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Therefore, the narrative suggests, investing in any solar manufacturer or new EV startup is a guaranteed, morally righteous path to generational wealth.", start: 2510.15, end: 2517.45),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The story feels so good.", start: 2518.01, end: 2519.35),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It feels like buying into the dawn of the automotive age in 1910.", start: 2519.89, end: 2522.27),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Because everyday investors desperately want to align their money with their morals—and get rich doing it—they willingly suspend their disbelief.", start: 2523.81, end: 2529.52),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They ignore the cold data: that manufacturing hardware is a brutally low-margin, capital-intensive business.", start: 2530.06, end: 2535.12),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They completely dismiss the historical reality that in massive industrial revolutions, the early pioneers usually go completely bankrupt fighting vicious price wars before the ultimate winners emerge.", start: 2535.62, end: 2544.36),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The fiction is that a necessary global transition automatically equals a profitable, risk-free investment for you.", start: 2544.98, end: 2551.78),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It doesn't.", start: 2552.36, end: 2552.82),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But when you desperately want to secure your financial future while feeling like you are saving the planet, the \"Green Super-Cycle\" becomes your oasis.", start: 2553.38, end: 2560.52),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You believe the hype not because the financial fundamentals support the valuation, but because you deeply need the story to be true.", start: 2561.12, end: 2567.26),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Protecting your portfolio means realizing that just because an industry changes the world, doesn't mean it will make you rich.", start: 2567.94, end: 2573.86),
                ]),
            ],
            12: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Walk into any bookstore or log onto any financial forum, and you will immediately notice a common delusion: everyone is desperately searching for the \"master key.\"", start: 2586.82, end: 2595.64),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The current state of the global market is a chaotic swirl of conflicting data, and in response, a multi-billion-dollar industry has emerged to sell you the illusion of a single, mathematically perfect formula.", start: 2596.42, end: 2607.2),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The friction that destroys everyday investors is the quiet, nagging belief that if they are struggling, it is simply because they haven't discovered the right algorithm or the correct spreadsheet yet.", start: 2608.08, end: 2617.54),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But personal finance is not physics; there are no universal laws that apply equally to every single person.", start: 2618.26, end: 2623.8),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "What works brilliantly for a billionaire hedge fund manager with a forty-year time horizon will completely bankrupt a thirty-year-old teacher saving for a down payment.", start: 2624.58, end: 2632.06),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The failure rate in personal wealth creation has very little to do with poor mathematics.", start: 2632.88, end: 2636.98),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It has everything to do with adopting a strategy that fundamentally clashes with your unique psychological makeup.", start: 2637.34, end: 2642.64),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You cannot borrow someone else's financial philosophy any more than you can borrow their personality.", start: 2643.46, end: 2647.64),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Sleep Test", start: 2648.42, end: 2649.18),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author tells a highly revealing story about his own personal finances to illustrate this exact point.", start: 2649.94, end: 2654.72),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you were to ask a high-powered supercomputer to design an investment portfolio for a young, high-income financial writer, the machine would output a very specific set of instructions.", start: 2655.54, end: 2664.13),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It would tell him to heavily leverage cheap debt, maximize his risk profile in the markets, and optimize every single dollar for the highest possible yield.", start: 2664.81, end: 2672.19),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Instead, the author does the exact opposite.", start: 2672.79, end: 2675.89),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He owns his house outright, refusing to carry a mortgage, and he keeps an uncomfortably large portion of his net worth sitting quietly in a standard bank account as plain, boring cash.", start: 2676.57, end: 2687.25),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "A purely rational economist would look at this and scream.", start: 2688.25, end: 2690.99),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They would point to the spreadsheets proving that the author is losing out on massive compound interest and allowing inflation to slowly eat away at his cash reserves.", start: 2691.81, end: 2699.63),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But the author argues that he is not trying to win a spreadsheet competition.", start: 2700.55, end: 2704.15),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He is trying to win the \"sleep test.\"", start: 2704.71, end: 2706.49),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "His personal philosophy is not optimized for maximum financial returns; it is optimized for independence and total peace of mind.", start: 2707.49, end: 2714.79),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He knows his own psychology.", start: 2715.69, end: 2716.95),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He knows that if a market crash wiped out his portfolio while he was heavily in debt, he would panic.", start: 2717.59, end: 2721.97),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "By paying off his house and holding cash, he has built a financial fortress that prevents him from ever being forced to make a desperate decision.", start: 2722.93, end: 2729.25),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He chose a strategy that is technically sub-optimal in a spreadsheet, but wildly successful in real life, because it allows his family to sleep soundly at night.", start: 2730.19, end: 2737.69),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Robotic Sky", start: 2738.71, end: 2739.59),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Today, the pressure to abandon your peace of mind for the sake of optimization is louder and more aggressive than ever.", start: 2740.57, end: 2746.03),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Look at the bleeding edge of the market right now: the explosive emergence of autonomous robotics and the rapidly developing eVTOL (electric vertical takeoff and landing) sector.", start: 2746.99, end: 2755.93),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The narratives surrounding these technologies are intoxicating.", start: 2756.51, end: 2759.81),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Social media feeds are flooded with aggressively smart analysts screaming that if you aren’t heavily exposed to the robotic supply chain or the new aerial mobility infrastructure, you are mathematically dooming your future.", start: 2760.53, end: 2771.33),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They present compelling, undeniable data showing how these sectors will reshape global transportation and labor.", start: 2771.87, end: 2777.41),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But here is where you must apply the author's logic: if putting a massive chunk of your net worth into a pre-revenue flying car startup makes you check your phone fifty times a day in a cold sweat, it is the wrong strategy for you.", start: 2777.85, end: 2789.45),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It does not matter if the math is right.", start: 2789.89, end: 2791.65),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Even if that specific eVTOL company goes on to completely dominate the sky in 2035, the extreme volatility between now and then will shake you out.", start: 2792.21, end: 2800.75),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You cannot reap the rewards of a mathematical home run if your psychological threshold forces you to abandon the game during the third inning.", start: 2801.19, end: 2807.82),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Your financial philosophy must act as a titanium filter against the noise of the \"next big thing.\"", start: 2808.32, end: 2813.18),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "True wealth management in the modern era is recognizing that a boring, conservative portfolio that you can stick with during a terrifying market crash will infinitely outperform a genius-level robotics portfolio that causes you to panic-exit at the exact wrong moment.", start: 2813.72, end: 2826.86),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You must define your own psychological breaking point and architect your entire financial life to ensure you never cross it.", start: 2827.48, end: 2833.52),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Final Words for the Book", start: 2834.1, end: 2835.22),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Psychology of Money reveals the ultimate paradox of finance: the most complex systems in the world are governed by the simplest human emotions.", start: 2835.64, end: 2844.74),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Intelligence, pedigree, and access to sophisticated data algorithms cannot save you from your own ego, fear, or greed.", start: 2845.44, end: 2852.78),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "True wealth is never measured by the car in your driveway or the notifications on your screen.", start: 2853.82, end: 2858.52),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It is measured by the invisible, quiet reality of waking up every single morning and knowing that you have total control over your own time.", start: 2859.24, end: 2867.3),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Master your psychology, respect the role of luck, build an unbreakable margin of safety, and you will achieve the only financial goal that actually matters: absolute freedom.", start: 2868.12, end: 2878.22),
                ]),
            ],
        ],
        4: [
            1: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The \"Smart Money\" Myth", start: 8.7, end: 9.8),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Come closer.", start: 11.18, end: 11.68),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Let’s be honest about why you’re nervous.", start: 12.02, end: 13.76),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You think the game is rigged.", start: 14.28, end: 15.84),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You look at the guys in the glass towers with their Bloomberg terminals, high-frequency trading algorithms, and billion-dollar research budgets, and you feel like a minnow swimming with sharks.", start: 16.36, end: 25.82),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You assume that to win, you need to play their game.", start: 26.44, end: 29.44),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But that is exactly why most retail investors get slaughtered—they try to imitate the \"pros\" without realizing that the pros are actually handcuffed.", start: 30.02, end: 38.0),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Institutional Handcuffs", start: 39.44, end: 40.86),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Peter Lynch, the legend who ran the Magellan Fund, used to laugh about this.", start: 42.14, end: 45.9),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He described the \"institutional imperative\" that paralyzes professional fund managers.", start: 46.42, end: 50.6),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Imagine a fund manager at a cocktail party.", start: 51.14, end: 52.98),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He explains that he can’t just buy a stock because it’s profitable; he has to buy what is \"acceptable.\"", start: 53.48, end: 58.46),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Lynch famously noted that \"You never get fired for losing money on IBM.\"", start: 60.16, end: 64.02),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If a manager buys IBM and it tanks, his boss shrugs—everyone holds IBM.", start: 64.62, end: 68.86),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But if that same manager buys a small, obscure company like a donut chain or a motel franchise, and that tanks?", start: 69.38, end: 75.26),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He’s fired for gambling.", start: 75.6, end: 76.78),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "By the time an institution is \"allowed\" to buy a high-growth stock, the company has usually been performing well for years.", start: 77.39, end: 83.11),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The \"Smart Money\" is actually the \"Late Money.\"", start: 83.59, end: 85.77),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They are forced to wait until the coast is clear, leaving the biggest gains on the table for the flexible amateur who saw the lines out the door three years earlier.", start: 86.19, end: 93.71),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The ETF Blindspot", start: 95.27, end: 96.53),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This dynamic is even more aggressive in the modern era.", start: 97.03, end: 99.83),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Today, the market is dominated by passive ETFs and Index Funds.", start: 100.37, end: 104.17),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "These funds operate on rigid rules—they must buy the biggest companies (like Apple or NVIDIA) regardless of valuation, and they cannot touch companies below a certain market cap.", start: 104.73, end: 114.73),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Think about the early days of Zoom or specialized AI tools.", start: 115.59, end: 118.81),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You might use a new piece of software at work every day, loving how it solves a problem.", start: 119.41, end: 123.49),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Meanwhile, Wall Street analysts can’t cover it yet because it’s too small, and the ETFs can’t buy it because it’s not in the S&P 500.", start: 123.99, end: 130.13),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This creates a massive inefficiency.", start: 131.33, end: 133.27),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "While the algorithms are fighting over fractions of a penny on Tesla, you have free reign in the under-followed small-cap market.", start: 133.81, end: 139.81),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Your lack of a \"compliance department\" is your greatest competitive advantage.", start: 140.37, end: 143.81),
                ]),
            ],
            2: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Casino Fallacy", start: 159.45, end: 160.51),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Most people treat the stock market like a casino, hoping for a lucky spin, but panicking the moment the dealer takes a chip.", start: 162.41, end: 168.99),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They buy high because their neighbor made a killing, and sell low because the news anchor looked worried.", start: 169.65, end: 174.43),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They fail not because they lack intelligence or data, but because they lack stomach.", start: 175.05, end: 179.27),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They haven't asked themselves the only question that matters before opening a brokerage account: \"What will I do when—not if—my portfolio drops 50%?\"", start: 179.85, end: 187.87),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you don't have an answer, you are already the market's prey.", start: 189.25, end: 192.15),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Stomach Over the Brain", start: 195.01, end: 196.38),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Peter Lynch calls this \"The Mirror Test.\"", start: 198.88, end: 200.94),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Before buying a single share, you must stand in front of a mirror and ask yourself three questions: \"Do I own a house?", start: 201.54, end: 208.08),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Do I need the money before I can get it back?", start: 208.62, end: 210.42),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Do I have the personal qualities that will bring me success?\"", start: 211.04, end: 213.64),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Lynch tells the story of the frantic calls he’d get during market crashes.", start: 214.48, end: 217.72),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Even when his fund, Magellan, was the best performing in the world, the average investor in his fund actually lost money.", start: 218.38, end: 224.88),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Why? because they bought in when he was on the cover of a magazine and sold out the moment the market dipped.", start: 225.48, end: 230.82),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They treated the stock market like a savings account that pays 15% interest.", start: 231.44, end: 235.12),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It doesn't.", start: 235.62, end: 236.04),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He explains that the most important organ for investing isn't the brain; it's the stomach.", start: 236.64, end: 241.24),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you are susceptible to selling everything in a panic because \"The Big One\" is coming, you should never buy a stock in the first place.", start: 241.86, end: 248.04),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You are better off in a money market fund than being right about a company but wrong about your own psychology.", start: 248.66, end: 253.66),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Gamification Trap", start: 256.14, end: 257.28),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This \"stomach\" problem has only intensified in the age of instant information and gamified trading apps.", start: 257.88, end: 263.88),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In Lynch's day, you had to call a broker to sell; that friction saved people from themselves.", start: 264.54, end: 269.58),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Today, you can liquidate your life savings from a notification on your watch while waiting for a latte.", start: 270.16, end: 275.66),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Consider the \"Crypto crashes\" or the meme-stock frenzies.", start: 276.28, end: 279.37),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Investors with high conviction in the technology (like blockchain) often get flushed out by 80% drawdowns because they used leverage or money they needed for next month's rent.", start: 279.95, end: 289.61),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The volatility is the price of admission for the returns.", start: 290.27, end: 293.17),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you are constantly checking your portfolio app, getting a dopamine hit when it's green and a cortisol spike when it's red, you are failing the Mirror Test every single day.", start: 293.85, end: 303.03),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You are confusing volatility (the price moving around) with risk (permanent loss of capital).", start: 303.71, end: 309.05),
                ]),
            ],
            3: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Prediction Addiction", start: 322.67, end: 323.95),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The single biggest waste of time for any investor is trying to predict the economy.", start: 324.57, end: 329.21),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You sit there, paralyzed, watching CNBC, terrified because the Fed might raise rates by a quarter point or because some pundit says a recession is \"imminent\" (they’ve been saying that for six years).", start: 329.81, end: 340.95),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You think you’re being responsible by waiting for the \"right time\" when the skies clear.", start: 341.53, end: 345.89),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But here is the brutal truth: the skies never clear.", start: 346.45, end: 349.61),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "There is always something to worry about.", start: 350.01, end: 351.69),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you spend 13 minutes a year thinking about economics, you've wasted 10 minutes.", start: 352.19, end: 356.71),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Cocktail Party Indicator", start: 358.0, end: 359.28),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Peter Lynch loved to poke fun at the \"The Great Worry.\"", start: 359.82, end: 362.74),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He tells the story of how, in the 1950s, people were terrified of a nuclear war and a depression; in the 1970s, it was oil prices; in the 1980s, it was Japan taking over the world.", start: 363.3, end: 373.8),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "There was never a year where a sensible person couldn’t find a dozen logical reasons to sell everything and hide under the bed.", start: 374.32, end: 380.36),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Lynch illustrated this with his \"Cocktail Party Theory.\"", start: 381.04, end: 383.24),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When he’d go to a party during a market bottom, no one wanted to talk about stocks; they talked about dentistry or the weather.", start: 383.78, end: 389.26),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When the market was up 15%, they’d ask him for tips.", start: 389.7, end: 392.18),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When the market was at a dangerous peak, they were giving him tips.", start: 392.56, end: 395.14),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "His point was simple: the crowd is always reacting to what has happened, not what will happen.", start: 395.58, end: 400.7),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He famously said, \"If you could predict the economy, you'd be a billionaire.\"", start: 401.18, end: 404.52),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Since you can't, you must ignore the macro and focus entirely on the micro: the specific earnings of the company in front of you.", start: 404.94, end: 411.54),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Doom-Scrolling Tax", start: 412.78, end: 413.88),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This is even harder today because the \"noise\" has become a deafening roar.", start: 414.4, end: 418.8),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In Lynch's time, you had the evening news.", start: 419.5, end: 421.7),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Today, you have a 24/7 feed of \"doom-scrolling\" on X (Twitter) and YouTube thumbnails screaming \"MARKET COLLAPSE IMMINENT!\"", start: 422.2, end: 430.38),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Think about the COVID-19 crash.", start: 431.34, end: 432.96),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Macro-economists predicted a decade-long depression.", start: 433.48, end: 436.39),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you listened to the macro noise, you sold everything.", start: 436.95, end: 439.53),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But if you ignored the economy and looked at the micro, you saw that companies like Zoom, Peloton, and Amazon were seeing explosive, unprecedented demand.", start: 440.07, end: 449.09),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The economy was closed, but specific businesses were booming.", start: 449.73, end: 452.97),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The same applies to AI today.", start: 453.63, end: 455.07),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "While pundits argue about a \"soft landing\" or \"hard landing\" for the GDP, specific companies are deploying LLMs and revolutionizing productivity regardless of what the Fed does next week.", start: 455.55, end: 466.25),
                ]),
            ],
            4: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Wall Street Gatekeeper", start: 479.55, end: 480.87),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You probably think the best stock tips are hidden in a locked room on Wall Street, guarded by men in $5,000 suits whispering about \"proprietary data.\"", start: 482.13, end: 490.69),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "So you ignore the most powerful investment tool you own: your eyes.", start: 491.45, end: 495.37),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You walk right past the next Apple or Starbucks every single day, use their products, complain about their competitors, and then go home to buy a stock you’ve never heard of because a stranger on the internet said it was \"ready to pop.\"", start: 496.11, end: 508.37),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This is madness.", start: 508.97, end: 509.95),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The best research isn't on a spreadsheet; it's in your shopping cart.", start: 510.59, end: 514.05),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Pantyhose Advantage", start: 515.08, end: 516.44),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Peter Lynch loved to humiliate the professional class with this concept.", start: 517.56, end: 520.88),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He tells the story of Hanes, the company that made L’eggs pantyhose.", start: 521.42, end: 524.78),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In the 1970s, Wall Street analysts were busy crunching numbers on steel mills and solar energy.", start: 525.42, end: 530.48),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Meanwhile, Lynch’s wife, Carolyn, came home raving about these new pantyhose sold in plastic eggs at the grocery store.", start: 531.08, end: 537.26),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They fit better, they were convenient, and she bought them every week.", start: 537.74, end: 540.66),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Lynch didn't run a complex discounted cash flow model initially.", start: 541.42, end: 544.32),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He just looked at the checkout line.", start: 544.76, end: 546.04),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He saw women buying them in droves.", start: 546.36, end: 548.24),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He realized that Hanes had a monopoly on the \"supermarket pantyhose\" niche.", start: 548.76, end: 552.26),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "While the \"smart money\" was ignoring a boring clothing company, the stock went up six-fold.", start: 552.84, end: 557.5),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He applied the same logic to Dunkin’ Donuts.", start: 558.18, end: 560.0),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He didn't need an annual report to tell him the coffee was good; he just saw that the parking lot was full at 6:00 AM every single morning.", start: 560.48, end: 566.32),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you like the product, chances are millions of others do too.", start: 566.86, end: 569.68),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The \"User Experience\" Alpha", start: 570.78, end: 572.22),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In the digital age, this \"local knowledge\" advantage has exploded.", start: 572.64, end: 576.66),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You don't just shop at the mall; you work in specialized software environments and live in digital ecosystems.", start: 577.32, end: 583.84),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Think about the rise of Slack or CrowdStrike.", start: 584.74, end: 587.44),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Who knew about these first?", start: 587.98, end: 589.2),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Not the bankers.", start: 589.72, end: 590.42),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It was the IT professionals and office workers who started using them and realized, \"Wow, this is actually essential.\"", start: 590.9, end: 596.87),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Or consider the Ozempic/Wegovy craze.", start: 597.81, end: 600.07),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Long before the stock chart went parabolic, ordinary people in gyms and doctor’s offices were whispering about a \"miracle shot\" for weight loss.", start: 600.63, end: 608.25),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you were a receptionist at a clinic or just a person struggling with weight, you had the \"insider info\" months before the hedge funds caught on.", start: 608.91, end: 616.31),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Your job, your hobbies, and your subscriptions are a goldmine of data that Wall Street can't access until the quarterly report comes out.", start: 616.97, end: 624.21),
                ]),
            ],
            5: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Seduction of \"Sexy\"", start: 639.15, end: 640.61),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You are addicted to \"sexy.\"", start: 641.73, end: 643.25),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You want to own the company that’s curing cancer, mining asteroids, or inventing the next iPhone.", start: 644.01, end: 649.31),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You want a stock ticker you can drop into a conversation at a dinner party that makes you look sophisticated and plugged-in.", start: 649.95, end: 655.57),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But here is the secret that will make you rich while your sophisticated friends go broke: excitement is expensive.", start: 656.29, end: 662.27),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If a company is \"hot,\" it’s already overpriced.", start: 662.99, end: 665.71),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The path to massive wealth is paved with boredom, disgust, and toxic waste.", start: 666.51, end: 670.91),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Funeral Home Moat", start: 672.23, end: 673.35),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Peter Lynch didn’t just tolerate boring companies; he fetishized them.", start: 674.57, end: 678.17),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He tells the story of his absolute dream stock: Service Corporation International (SCI).", start: 678.87, end: 684.41),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "What did they do?", start: 685.07, end: 685.53),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They buried people.", start: 686.11, end: 686.95),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They were a funeral home chain.", start: 687.27, end: 688.41),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Lynch loved SCI because it hit every single one of his \"Perfect Stock\" criteria: it had a boring name, it did something disagreeable (nobody likes thinking about death), and rumors about the industry were depressing.", start: 689.69, end: 700.45),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Wall Street analysts refused to cover it because they didn't want to call their clients and say, \"I've got a great deal on coffins.\"", start: 701.27, end: 706.49),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Because the pros ignored it, the stock price stayed low relative to its earnings for years, allowing Lynch to buy in cheap while the company quietly bought up mom-and-pop funeral homes across the country, compounding its value in the shadows.", start: 707.37, end: 718.28),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He jokingly said if he could find a company with a name like \"Bob’s Toxic Waste & Septic Tank Cleaning,\" he’d buy it immediately.", start: 719.32, end: 725.16),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Boredom Arbitrage", start: 726.42, end: 727.5),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This \"Boredom Arbitrage\" is even more potent today because the \"hype cycle\" moves faster than ever.", start: 728.72, end: 733.22),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When \"AI\" became the buzzword, stocks like NVIDIA and Microsoft skyrocketed instantly.", start: 733.96, end: 738.26),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The premiums were priced in within seconds.", start: 738.98, end: 740.7),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But look at the \"plumbing\" of the modern world.", start: 741.34, end: 743.6),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "While everyone was betting on volatile crypto exchanges, companies like Waste Management (WM) or Cintas (CTAS) (uniform rentals) were printing money.", start: 744.08, end: 751.84),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Think about Costco.", start: 752.5, end: 753.36),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It’s a warehouse.", start: 753.86, end: 754.72),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It sells bulk toilet paper.", start: 754.86, end: 756.28),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It is the definition of unsexy.", start: 756.68, end: 758.68),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Yet, it has crushed the performance of most \"disruptive\" tech stocks over the long run because it dominates a niche, has a recurring revenue model (memberships), and is too boring for the \"get rich quick\" crowd to pump and dump.", start: 759.26, end: 770.52),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In the software world, look for the unsexy B2B SaaS companies that handle payroll or compliance—the stuff that has to happen for the economy to function, regardless of whether ChatGPT takes over the world.", start: 771.18, end: 781.94),
                ]),
            ],
            6: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The One-Size-Fits-All Error", start: 793.04, end: 794.86),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You are judging a fish by its ability to climb a tree.", start: 795.42, end: 798.24),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You buy a utility company and get angry when it doesn't double in six months.", start: 798.88, end: 802.54),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You buy a high-growth tech stock and panic when it drops 20% in a week.", start: 803.18, end: 806.78),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You are losing money because you are applying the same rules to completely different games.", start: 807.44, end: 811.68),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You treat every ticker symbol as a \"stock,\" but that is like treating a racehorse, a dairy cow, and a house cat as just \"animals.\"", start: 812.22, end: 819.12),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you try to milk the racehorse, you’re going to get kicked.", start: 819.66, end: 821.94),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Taxonomy of Profit", start: 822.64, end: 824.0),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Peter Lynch stopped this madness by creating a strict taxonomy.", start: 824.72, end: 827.86),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Before he bought a single share, he forced the company into one of six boxes: Slow Growers, Stalwarts, Fast Growers, Cyclicals, Asset Plays, or Turnarounds.", start: 828.4, end: 838.34),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He tells the story of how this saved him with the auto industry.", start: 838.94, end: 841.48),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Most people treated car companies like \"Stalwarts\" (steady reliable growers like Coca-Cola).", start: 842.02, end: 846.22),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Lynch recognized them as \"Cyclicals\"—companies whose fortunes rise and fall with the economy.", start: 846.8, end: 851.08),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When Ford was booming, amateurs bought more, thinking the growth was permanent.", start: 851.6, end: 855.04),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Lynch sold, knowing the cycle would inevitably turn.", start: 855.42, end: 857.88),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He viewed \"Fast Growers\" (like Taco Bell in its early days) as the only ones worth holding through volatility, whereas \"Turnarounds\" (like Chrysler) were pure plays on survival, not growth.", start: 858.44, end: 867.69),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you don't know which category your stock is in, you don't know when to sell.", start: 868.23, end: 871.51),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Identity Crisis", start: 872.23, end: 873.21),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In the modern market, misclassification is the primary cause of portfolio death.", start: 873.61, end: 878.41),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Look at Zoom or Peloton during the pandemic.", start: 878.93, end: 881.19),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Millions of investors mistook them for \"Fast Growers\" (permanent secular trends).", start: 881.73, end: 886.05),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In reality, they were \"Cyclicals\" tied to the \"stay-at-home\" cycle.", start: 886.51, end: 889.75),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When the world reopened, the cycle turned, and the stocks collapsed.", start: 890.21, end: 893.43),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The same applies to Crypto Miners.", start: 893.95, end: 895.49),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They are not \"tech growth stocks\"; they are commodity cyclicals tied to the price of Bitcoin.", start: 895.87, end: 900.23),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If Bitcoin drops, their earnings vanish.", start: 900.65, end: 902.55),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Conversely, Microsoft and Apple have transitioned from Fast Growers to \"Stalwarts.\"", start: 903.11, end: 907.33),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They won't make you rich overnight anymore, but they offer recession protection that a small-cap AI startup simply cannot.", start: 907.71, end: 913.51),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Match the Strategy", start: 914.63, end: 915.47),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Cyclicals (Chips, Energy, Crypto): Sell when P/E is low (earnings are at peak).", start: 916.09, end: 921.05),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Fast Growers (AI, SaaS): Hold as long as the earnings growth story is intact.", start: 921.55, end: 926.35),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Stalwarts (Big Tech): Sell if the valuation gets absurd (e.g., 80x earnings).", start: 926.79, end: 931.17),
                ]),
            ],
            7: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Price Tag Distraction", start: 941.37, end: 942.55),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You are hypnotized by the wrong number.", start: 943.49, end: 945.35),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You wake up, check your phone, and see a stock price.", start: 946.11, end: 948.67),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It’s up $5.", start: 949.27, end: 949.49),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You feel brilliant.", start: 950.47, end: 951.23),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It’s down $10.", start: 951.79, end: 952.27),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You feel like a failure.", start: 953.27, end: 954.17),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You are letting the market’s mood swings dictate your emotional state.", start: 954.91, end: 958.15),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This is because you view a stock as a piece of paper that magically changes value, rather than what it actually is: a claim on a stream of cash.", start: 958.83, end: 966.85),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you don't know exactly how the company makes a dollar of profit, you are walking blindfolded into traffic.", start: 967.59, end: 972.81),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Two-Minute Drill", start: 973.69, end: 974.4),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Peter Lynch had a simple cure for price-fixation: the \"Two-Minute Drill.\"", start: 975.34, end: 978.8),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Before buying, he forced himself to deliver a monologue.", start: 979.54, end: 982.24),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If he couldn't explain to a child in two minutes why the company's earnings were going to go up, he wouldn't buy.", start: 982.84, end: 988.14),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He loved to show charts where the stock price line wobbled all over the place like a drunk, while the earnings line climbed steadily upward like a staircase.", start: 988.9, end: 995.9),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "His point?", start: 996.54, end: 996.9),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The drunk (price) eventually has to come home to the staircase (earnings).", start: 997.48, end: 1001.38),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If a company’s earnings grow by 20% a year for a decade, the stock price will eventually follow, regardless of wars, recessions, or bad moods on Wall Street.", start: 1002.12, end: 1010.2),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He famously said, \"If you can’t predict the earnings, you can’t predict the stock.\"", start: 1010.86, end: 1014.64),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He didn't care about the \"story\" unless the story ended in a check being cashed.", start: 1015.28, end: 1019.02),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The \"Profitless Prosperity\" Myth", start: 1019.76, end: 1021.2),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In the modern era, Silicon Valley has tried to convince you that \"Earnings don't matter\"—that \"Growth\" and \"Users\" and \"Total Addressable Market\" are the new metrics.", start: 1021.78, end: 1030.98),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This is a trap.", start: 1031.62, end: 1032.52),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Look at the SaaS (Software as a Service) boom of 2020-2021.", start: 1033.24, end: 1036.0),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Companies like Snowflake or Asana were trading at 50x or 100x revenue while losing millions of dollars.", start: 1038.1, end: 1044.54),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Investors said, \"It's a new paradigm!\"", start: 1045.14, end: 1047.09),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Then interest rates rose, and the floor fell out.", start: 1047.73, end: 1050.33),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The stocks that survived and thrived (like Microsoft or Alphabet) were the ones with massive, undeniable profits.", start: 1051.09, end: 1057.61),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Even Uber, the poster child for \"growth at all costs,\" only became a stable investment once it proved it could actually generate positive cash flow.", start: 1058.31, end: 1066.43),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The \"earnings engine\" is the only thing that keeps a stock afloat when the hype cycle ends.", start: 1067.13, end: 1071.59),
                ]),
            ],
            8: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Balance Sheet Blindness", start: 1085.39, end: 1087.03),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You are driving a sports car at 150 miles per hour, but you’ve taped over the fuel gauge because \"math is boring.\"", start: 1088.25, end: 1095.05),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You love the speed—the rising stock price, the hype, the revolutionary technology.", start: 1095.73, end: 1100.47),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But you are ignoring the only thing that can kill you instantly: running out of gas.", start: 1101.11, end: 1105.93),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Most investors treat the Balance Sheet like a terms-and-conditions document—they scroll right past it.", start: 1107.25, end: 1112.33),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They assume that if a company is \"changing the world,\" the money will sort itself out.", start: 1113.01, end: 1117.61),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This is a fatal error.", start: 1118.23, end: 1119.31),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Companies don't go bankrupt because they lack vision; they go bankrupt because they run out of cash.", start: 1119.93, end: 1124.79),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you cannot spot the difference between a company that is \"investing in growth\" and one that is bleeding to death, you are not an investor; you are a philanthropist for bad management.", start: 1125.57, end: 1134.66),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Debt Detective", start: 1135.98, end: 1136.96),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Peter Lynch approached the balance sheet not like an accountant, but like a detective at a crime scene.", start: 1138.14, end: 1142.64),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He wasn't looking for \"perfect\" numbers; he was looking for the \"murder weapon\"—usually Debt.", start: 1143.18, end: 1147.38),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He tells the story of Chrysler in the early 1980s.", start: 1148.6, end: 1151.1),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Everyone thought the company was dead.", start: 1151.64, end: 1153.0),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The stock was trading at miserable lows.", start: 1153.4, end: 1155.18),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But Lynch dug into the debt structure and found a crucial detail that the market missed: Chrysler’s debt was mostly \"funded debt\" (long-term bonds), not \"bank debt\" (loans the bank can call in immediately).", start: 1155.82, end: 1166.28),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This meant Chrysler had time to turn the ship around.", start: 1166.94, end: 1169.16),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The banks couldn't force them into bankruptcy overnight.", start: 1169.54, end: 1171.74),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He also obsessed over Inventory.", start: 1172.02, end: 1174.08),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Lynch would look at a company’s sales growth versus its inventory growth.", start: 1174.76, end: 1178.24),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If sales were up 10% but inventory was up 30%, he ran for the exit.", start: 1178.8, end: 1183.58),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Why?", start: 1184.22, end: 1184.48),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Because it meant the company was stuffing warehouses with products nobody wanted.", start: 1184.98, end: 1188.68),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In the retail world, unsold inventory is like rotting fish—the longer it sits, the more it stinks, and eventually, you have to pay someone to take it away (mark it down to zero).", start: 1189.32, end: 1198.86),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He viewed a buildup of inventory as the single most reliable \"sell signal\" in the market, often appearing months before the stock price collapsed.", start: 1199.62, end: 1207.06),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The ZIRP Zombie Apocalypse", start: 1208.94, end: 1210.56),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In the last decade, we lived through a \"Zero Interest Rate Policy\" (ZIRP) fantasy world where debt was free.", start: 1211.28, end: 1217.44),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This created an entire generation of \"Zombie Companies\"—tech startups and growth stocks that survived only by constantly borrowing cheap money or issuing new shares.", start: 1218.1, end: 1227.14),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They had great revenue growth but terrible balance sheets.", start: 1227.68, end: 1230.34),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Now that interest rates have normalized, the tide has gone out, and we can see who is swimming naked.", start: 1231.1, end: 1235.67),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Look at the collapse of WeWork or the struggles of Peloton.", start: 1236.27, end: 1238.87),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "These companies had incredible \"stories\" and \"revenue growth,\" but their balance sheets were ticking time bombs.", start: 1239.47, end: 1244.47),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They were burning cash faster than they could bring it in.", start: 1244.93, end: 1247.07),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Today, \"Financial Forensics\" means looking past the \"Adjusted EBITDA\" (which Charlie Munger famously called \"bullshit earnings\") and looking at Free Cash Flow.", start: 1249.07, end: 1257.61),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In the SaaS (Software as a Service) world, look at the \"Burn Rate.\"", start: 1257.61, end: 1260.15),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If a company has $100 million in the bank but burns $50 million a quarter, they have six months to live.", start: 1260.65, end: 1266.29),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "No amount of \"AI integration\" announcements can save a company that cannot pay its server bills.", start: 1266.87, end: 1271.29),
                ]),
            ],
            9: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Empire Builder Complex", start: 1288.59, end: 1289.99),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You love a charismatic CEO.", start: 1290.83, end: 1292.49),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You watch them on TV, radiating confidence, talking about \"synergies\" and \"ecosystems,\" and you think, \"This guy is a visionary.\"", start: 1293.05, end: 1300.21),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You are falling for the oldest trick in the book.", start: 1300.83, end: 1302.93),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Most managers, when left unsupervised with a pile of cash, do not act like responsible stewards; they act like emperors.", start: 1303.61, end: 1309.83),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They get bored with the core business that made them rich and start looking for excitement.", start: 1310.47, end: 1314.15),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They want to buy a movie studio, a sports team, or a competitor they don't understand, just to make their empire bigger.", start: 1314.65, end: 1320.19),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "And they use your money to do it.", start: 1320.63, end: 1322.19),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Diworsification Disease", start: 1323.07, end: 1324.57),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Peter Lynch had a name for this disease: \"Diworsification.\"", start: 1325.37, end: 1328.23),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He tells the story of companies that were printing money in a boring, profitable niche (like making razors or cigarettes) and then decided to \"diversify\" by buying completely unrelated businesses—like a razor company buying a turkey farm.", start: 1329.05, end: 1340.15),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Lynch viewed a high dividend not just as a payout, but as a \"discipline.\"", start: 1341.01, end: 1344.33),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If a company commits to paying a dividend, the CEO can't waste that cash on a foolish acquisition.", start: 1344.95, end: 1349.39),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The money is gone; it’s in your pocket.", start: 1349.73, end: 1351.73),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He loved the \"dull\" management teams that simply raised the dividend every year.", start: 1352.57, end: 1356.21),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It was a signal that the business was real.", start: 1356.72, end: 1358.36),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He famously said that while companies can fake earnings with accounting tricks, \"dividends don't lie.\"", start: 1358.96, end: 1363.32),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You either have the cash to pay them, or you don't.", start: 1363.7, end: 1365.64),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Buyback Charade", start: 1366.48, end: 1367.4),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In the modern tech world, \"Diworsification\" has a new face: \"Moonshots.\"", start: 1368.14, end: 1373.0),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Look at Meta (Facebook) in 2021-2022.", start: 1373.58, end: 1375.0),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They were generating billions in ad revenue, but instead of returning it to shareholders, they burned billions trying to build the \"Metaverse.\"", start: 1376.88, end: 1384.54),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The stock collapsed.", start: 1385.04, end: 1386.06),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It was only when Mark Zuckerberg cut costs and initiated a dividend in 2024 that the market truly forgave him.", start: 1386.6, end: 1393.2),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Today, the \"Dividend\" has a quieter, more tax-efficient cousin: the Stock Buyback.", start: 1394.34, end: 1399.48),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Companies like Apple don't just pay dividends; they use their massive cash piles to buy their own shares, reducing the share count and making your remaining shares more valuable.", start: 1400.08, end: 1409.0),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "However, you must watch out for the \"fake buyback\"—where a company buys back stock just to offset the millions of shares they gave to employees as \"Stock-Based Compensation.\"", start: 1409.58, end: 1419.08),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "That isn't returning capital; it's just treading water.", start: 1419.54, end: 1422.12),
                ]),
            ],
            10: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Watering the Weeds", start: 1433.98, end: 1434.9),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You are likely guilty of the most destructive habit in investing: \"Cutting the flowers and watering the weeds.\"", start: 1435.74, end: 1441.04),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You buy a stock, and it goes up 40%.", start: 1441.74, end: 1443.08),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You get nervous.", start: 1444.16, end: 1444.74),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You think, \"I better sell and lock in the profit before it disappears.\"", start: 1445.2, end: 1448.28),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Then you look at your other stock that is down 40%.", start: 1448.92, end: 1450.52),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You think, \"I can’t sell this one at a loss; I’ll wait for it to come back.\"", start: 1451.6, end: 1454.76),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "So, you sell the winner and keep the loser.", start: 1455.46, end: 1457.56),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You have just penalized success and rewarded failure.", start: 1458.22, end: 1460.94),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Over time, this leaves you with a portfolio full of stagnant \"weeds\" and zero \"flowers.\"", start: 1461.52, end: 1466.08),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You are managing your emotions, not your money.", start: 1466.66, end: 1468.69),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Concentration Edge", start: 1469.63, end: 1470.69),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Peter Lynch viewed portfolio management as gardening.", start: 1471.49, end: 1473.93),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He argued that there is no magic number of stocks to own, but there is a magic rule: only own what you can follow.", start: 1474.41, end: 1480.33),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He mocked the idea of \"diversification\" for its own sake, calling it \"diworsification.\"", start: 1481.01, end: 1485.35),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you have a distinct \"edge\" in only one company, own one.", start: 1485.99, end: 1488.65),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you find five great situations, own five.", start: 1489.15, end: 1491.43),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But don't buy a 10th stock just to \"spread risk\" if you don't know anything about it.", start: 1491.89, end: 1495.63),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Lynch’s strategy was to constantly rotate capital based on the \"story,\" not the price.", start: 1496.29, end: 1500.59),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If a \"Stalwart\" (steady grower) went up 50% and got expensive, he would sell it to buy a \"Fast Grower\" or a \"Turnaround\" that was just starting its journey.", start: 1501.15, end: 1508.19),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He didn't sell because the price was up; he sold because the opportunity had shifted to a better category.", start: 1508.79, end: 1513.37),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The \"Fake Diversification\" Trap", start: 1514.09, end: 1515.49),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In the modern ETF era, investors have fooled themselves into thinking they are diversified when they are actually just \"closet indexers.\"", start: 1516.11, end: 1524.43),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You might own an S&P 500 ETF, a \"Tech Growth\" ETF, and a \"US Momentum\" ETF.", start: 1525.07, end: 1531.71),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You think you have three distinct assets.", start: 1532.31, end: 1534.51),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In reality, all three are heavily weighted in NVIDIA, Microsoft, and Apple.", start: 1534.95, end: 1539.87),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You haven't diversified; you’ve just tripled your exposure to the same five companies.", start: 1540.41, end: 1544.8),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Similarly, \"Crypto Diversification\" is often a myth.", start: 1545.72, end: 1548.66),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Buying 20 different \"altcoins\" isn't diversification if they all crash 90% the moment Bitcoin sneezes.", start: 1549.22, end: 1555.56),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "True allocation today means understanding correlation.", start: 1556.28, end: 1559.46),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If everything in your portfolio turns green on the same day, you aren't diversified; you're just lucky.", start: 1560.02, end: 1565.28),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "A properly designed portfolio should have parts that zig when others zag—like holding cash or short-term treasuries to deploy when the \"Fast Growers\" crash.", start: 1565.96, end: 1574.18),
                ]),
            ],
            11: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Loyalty Penalty", start: 1584.96, end: 1585.98),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You treat your stocks like a marriage, sticking with them \"for better or worse\" long after the love is gone.", start: 1587.08, end: 1592.24),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You bought a company because it had a great new product three years ago.", start: 1593.08, end: 1595.74),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Today, competitors have flooded the market, the CEO quit, and profit margins are shrinking.", start: 1596.58, end: 1601.34),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Yet you still hold on, paralyzed by nostalgia.", start: 1601.96, end: 1604.62),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You are investing in a memory, not a business.", start: 1605.5, end: 1608.02),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The most dangerous phrase in your vocabulary is \"I’ll just hold it for the long term,\" because \"long term\" is often just a euphemism for \"I’m too lazy to check if the thesis is broken.\"", start: 1608.86, end: 1618.34),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Life-Cycle Audit", start: 1619.6, end: 1620.54),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Peter Lynch didn't \"buy and hold\"; he \"bought and watched.\"", start: 1621.62, end: 1624.92),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He treated his portfolio like a constantly evolving narrative.", start: 1625.76, end: 1628.94),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He tells the story of Holiday Inn.", start: 1629.76, end: 1631.18),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In the 1950s and 60s, it was a classic \"Fast Grower.\"", start: 1632.04, end: 1635.08),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You could travel across America and see them popping up at every exit.", start: 1635.76, end: 1638.66),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The stock was a rocket ship.", start: 1639.38, end: 1640.66),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But by the mid-70s, the growth phase was mathematically over—they were everywhere.", start: 1641.8, end: 1645.6),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "There was no more room to build.", start: 1645.86, end: 1647.06),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Lynch realized the \"story\" had changed.", start: 1648.24, end: 1650.14),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The company wasn't dying, but it had morphed from a sprinter into a slow jogger.", start: 1650.9, end: 1654.76),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The investors who kept expecting \"Fast Grower\" returns from a saturated \"Stalwart\" got crushed.", start: 1655.68, end: 1660.23),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He instituted a \"Two-Minute Drill\" re-check every few months.", start: 1661.07, end: 1664.21),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If the story had drifted—like a company moving from \"high growth\" to \"cyclical\"—he didn't hesitate to sell, even if he liked the stock.", start: 1665.01, end: 1671.35),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He knew that when the story ends, you have to leave the theater.", start: 1672.11, end: 1675.13),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Disruption Clock", start: 1676.59, end: 1677.47),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In the modern world, \"stories\" rot faster than ever.", start: 1678.29, end: 1681.31),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Technology accelerates the lifecycle of companies.", start: 1681.83, end: 1684.23),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Think about BlackBerry.", start: 1684.81, end: 1685.69),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "For years, it was the standard for business communication.", start: 1686.13, end: 1688.53),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It was a \"Fast Grower.\"", start: 1688.95, end: 1689.93),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Then the iPhone launched.", start: 1690.49, end: 1691.55),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The story didn't just change; it evaporated overnight.", start: 1691.97, end: 1694.69),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Investors who re-evaluated the \"moat\" (physical keyboards vs. touchscreens) got out.", start: 1695.31, end: 1699.71),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Those who relied on past glory (\"Everyone uses BBM!\") lost everything.", start: 1700.21, end: 1704.17),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The same happened with Peloton.", start: 1704.81, end: 1705.97),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The \"story\" was: \"Everyone is working out at home forever.\"", start: 1706.47, end: 1708.97),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Then gyms reopened.", start: 1709.49, end: 1710.43),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The story broke.", start: 1710.65, end: 1711.33),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you didn't re-evaluate immediately when vaccines rolled out, you rode the stock all the way down.", start: 1711.89, end: 1716.37),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Today, you must watch for \"AI Disruption.\"", start: 1717.03, end: 1719.17),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Is your \"Stalwart\" software company about to be automated away by a Large Language Model?", start: 1719.67, end: 1723.55),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If the fundamental \"why\" of your investment is threatened by a new technology, you must sell before the earnings report confirms the damage.", start: 1724.13, end: 1730.57),
                ]),
            ],
            12: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Emotional Inversion", start: 1742.01, end: 1743.39),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Buying a stock is like falling in love—it’s exciting, full of promise, and driven by dopamine.", start: 1744.29, end: 1749.35),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Selling a stock is like a divorce—it’s painful, confusing, and driven by fear.", start: 1749.91, end: 1754.47),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Most investors are terrible at \"the breakup.\"", start: 1755.13, end: 1757.27),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You sell your winners too early because you’re terrified the profit will vanish (locking in a small gain), and you hold your losers too long because you can’t admit you were wrong (praying for a rebound).", start: 1757.75, end: 1767.31),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You are emotionally inverted: you are loyal to the things that hurt you and fickle with the things that help you.", start: 1767.85, end: 1773.13),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You need a prenup for your portfolio.", start: 1773.65, end: 1775.49),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Cyclical Peak", start: 1776.63, end: 1777.61),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Peter Lynch didn’t believe in \"target prices.\"", start: 1778.43, end: 1780.59),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He believed in \"Category Signals.\"", start: 1780.93, end: 1782.59),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He realized that the signal to sell a fast-growing restaurant chain is completely different from the signal to sell a boring chemical company.", start: 1782.99, end: 1789.29),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He tells the story of the Cyclical Trap.", start: 1790.03, end: 1791.85),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Amateur investors love to buy Cyclicals (like auto companies or steel mills) when the P/E ratio is low, thinking they are getting a bargain.", start: 1792.49, end: 1799.25),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Lynch whispered the exact opposite: \"Sell the Cyclical when the P/E is low.\"", start: 1799.73, end: 1803.9),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Why?", start: 1804.24, end: 1804.48),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Because for a Cyclical, a low P/E means earnings are at a record high, the economy is booming, and everything is perfect.", start: 1805.08, end: 1811.24),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This is the top.", start: 1811.56, end: 1812.42),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The only place to go is down.", start: 1812.76, end: 1814.16),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Conversely, he advised holding Fast Growers (like a young Walmart or Taco Bell) even if the P/E looked high, provided the growth story was still intact.", start: 1814.78, end: 1822.26),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "As long as they were opening new stores and same-store sales were rising, he held on.", start: 1822.64, end: 1826.18),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He didn't sell because the stock went up; he sold only when the company stopped growing or the valuation became mathematically impossible (like a Stalwart trading at 50x earnings).", start: 1826.66, end: 1835.48),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Algorithmic Front-Run", start: 1835.98, end: 1837.14),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In today’s hyper-speed market, \"The Exit\" is even more critical because algorithms punish missed expectations instantly.", start: 1837.88, end: 1845.56),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Look at the Semiconductor Industry (NVIDIA, AMD).", start: 1846.38, end: 1849.1),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "These are the ultimate modern Cyclicals.", start: 1849.82, end: 1851.84),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When demand for AI chips is insatiable, their P/E ratios compress because earnings explode.", start: 1852.38, end: 1857.88),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "That is precisely the danger zone.", start: 1858.4, end: 1860.2),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you wait for the headlines to say \"Chip Shortage Over,\" the stock will have already dropped 40%.", start: 1860.76, end: 1865.04),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The market \"front-runs\" the cycle.", start: 1866.18, end: 1867.7),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Similarly, look at Crypto.", start: 1868.52, end: 1869.62),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The \"Sell the News\" phenomenon is real.", start: 1870.18, end: 1872.22),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When the Bitcoin ETF was finally approved in early 2024, the price dropped.", start: 1872.72, end: 1876.9),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Why?", start: 1877.3, end: 1877.54),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Because the anticipation was the trade.", start: 1877.96, end: 1879.82),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Once the event happened, the smart money exited into the liquidity provided by the retail crowd buying the headline.", start: 1880.36, end: 1885.58),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "And for the \"COVID Winners\" (Zoom, DocuSign): The sell signal wasn't the price; it was the return to the office.", start: 1886.34, end: 1892.76),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The moment the behavioral trend shifted, the \"Fast Grower\" thesis died, and the exit protocol should have triggered immediately, regardless of the loss.", start: 1893.28, end: 1900.84),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Final Words", start: 1901.98, end: 1902.58),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Wall Street has spent billions constructing an illusion designed to intimidate you, desperate to make you believe that beating the market requires a team of analysts, expensive terminals, or complex deep learning models predicting price movements.", start: 1903.22, end: 1916.64),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In reality, their massive size and rigid institutional compliance rules are their fatal flaws, forcing them to buy late and locking them out of the most lucrative early-stage growth.", start: 1917.24, end: 1927.93),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "By stripping away the macroeconomic noise and ignoring the seduction of \"sexy\" trends, you’ve discovered that your greatest competitive moat is your own daily life.", start: 1928.61, end: 1938.07),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The \"Smart Money\" is handcuffed, but you—the observant amateur—have the agility to spot the next massive winner in your shopping cart, your software stack, or your local neighborhood long before the index funds are allowed to buy in.", start: 1938.65, end: 1950.77),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Tomorrow morning, when the opening bell rings and the financial networks scream about the next imminent crisis, you are no longer the market's prey.", start: 1951.49, end: 1958.75),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You now operate with a ruthless, resilient system: you know how to leverage your local knowledge, run the financial forensics on an earnings engine, and execute strict exit protocols based on a company's true category rather than its stock price.", start: 1959.33, end: 1972.11),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You are no longer playing their gamified, high-frequency casino; you are playing the quiet, patient game of business ownership.", start: 1972.71, end: 1979.53),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "So, trust the balance sheet, and just look around you—the edge has been yours the whole time, and now you finally know how to master it.", start: 1980.05, end: 1986.71),
                ]),
            ],
        ],
        8: [
            1: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Here is the friction: most investors treat the stock market like a casino and their shares like betting chips.", start: 10.6, end: 17.44),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They obsess over the flashing numbers (the price), completely detached from the reality of what those numbers represent.", start: 18.0, end: 24.54),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When the \"chip\" value drops, they panic and fold.", start: 25.16, end: 28.1),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This is the \"Renter’s Mentality\"—you are just renting a position on a chart, hoping to pass it to a greater fool for a profit.", start: 28.8, end: 36.1),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This detachment is the single greatest cause of wealth destruction.", start: 36.84, end: 40.73),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You cannot weather a storm if you don't even know what house you are living in.", start: 41.35, end: 44.93),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The \"Silent Partner\" Letter Buffett flips this dynamic by ignoring the stock market entirely.", start: 46.85, end: 52.87),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In his foundational Owner-Related Business Principles, he tells a simple but radical story: imagine Berkshire Hathaway isn't a publicly traded corporation, but a private family partnership.", start: 53.49, end: 65.53),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He posits that he is the managing partner, and you are the silent partner.", start: 66.73, end: 70.77),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You aren't a \"shareholder\"—a faceless source of capital to be exploited—you are a co-owner.", start: 71.43, end: 76.85),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Buffett famously notes that he treats his investors as if they were his own sisters and aunts.", start: 77.59, end: 82.33),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "An owner of a private farm doesn't check the price of their land every day; they check the weather and the crop yield.", start: 83.01, end: 88.41),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Buffett teaches that if you wouldn't be comfortable owning a stock if the market closed down for five years, you shouldn't own it for five minutes.", start: 89.21, end: 96.21),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Gamification Trap", start: 96.91, end: 98.59),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In the modern era, \"Adopting the Owner's Mindset\" is harder—and more profitable—than ever.", start: 99.23, end: 105.31),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Financial apps have weaponized the \"Renter's Mentality\" through gamification.", start: 106.03, end: 110.67),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When you buy a stock on a modern app and see confetti explode, or panic-sell because a crypto coin dropped 15% in an hour, you are falling into the trap Buffett warned against.", start: 111.27, end: 123.0),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Apply the \"Owner's Mindset\" to the AI boom.", start: 124.06, end: 126.8),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The \"Renter\" buys NVIDIA because the line is going up.", start: 127.46, end: 130.8),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The \"Owner\" buys it because they understand the moat of the CUDA software ecosystem and want to own a proportional share of that cash flow for the next decade.", start: 131.36, end: 140.74),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you are stressing over quarterly earnings calls, you are likely speculating, not owning.", start: 141.52, end: 147.0),
                ]),
            ],
            2: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Profit Mirage", start: 160.24, end: 161.38),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Here is the dangerous secret about financial statements: \"Profit\" is an opinion, but \"Cash\" is a fact.", start: 162.52, end: 169.24),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Most aspiring investors glance at the bottom line of an Income Statement—Net Income—and assume that’s how much money the business actually made.", start: 170.18, end: 177.58),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They are wrong.", start: 178.08, end: 178.8),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "GAAP (Generally Accepted Accounting Principles) is a set of rules designed to make companies comparable, not necessarily truthful about their economic reality.", start: 180.02, end: 188.66),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You can follow every accounting rule perfectly and still go bankrupt while reporting a \"profit.\"", start: 189.56, end: 194.52),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you are analyzing a business based solely on its Price-to-Earnings (P/E) ratio, you are effectively driving a car by looking only at the speedometer while ignoring the fuel gauge.", start: 195.58, end: 204.9),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You know how fast you're going, but not when the engine is about to die.", start: 205.5, end: 208.64),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The \"Owner Earnings\" Revelation", start: 209.76, end: 211.34),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Buffett solved this by inventing his own metric: \"Owner Earnings.\"", start: 212.46, end: 216.06),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In his letters, he describes a hypothetical business that reports massive profits but requires new machinery every year just to stay open.", start: 217.16, end: 224.54),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "To the accountant, buying that machine is just capital expenditure (CapEx) that gets depreciated slowly over years.", start: 225.6, end: 231.54),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "To the owner, that money is gone.", start: 232.18, end: 233.96),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It left the bank account.", start: 234.32, end: 235.32),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It cannot be used to pay dividends or expand.", start: 235.64, end: 237.9),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Buffett’s formula is ruthless: Take reported earnings, add back depreciation (a non-cash charge), but then subtract the capital expenditures required to maintain the company's competitive position.", start: 239.0, end: 249.98),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This reveals the \"distributable cash\"—the actual money the owner can take out of the business without hurting it.", start: 251.14, end: 256.66),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He teaches us to look for companies that don't just report accounting profits, but generate \"free cash flow\"—businesses that don't require heavy reinvestment just to survive.", start: 257.75, end: 266.59),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The \"Adjusted EBITDA\" Trap", start: 266.99, end: 269.35),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In today’s tech-dominated market, this distortion is even worse.", start: 270.23, end: 274.35),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We live in the era of \"Adjusted EBITDA\"—a metric Charlie Munger famously called \"bullshit earnings.\"", start: 274.93, end: 282.01),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Modern tech companies (SaaS, AI, Gig Economy) often report massive losses but claim they are profitable on an \"Adjusted\" basis.", start: 282.85, end: 291.43),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They do this by excluding things like Stock-Based Compensation (paying employees in stock instead of cash).", start: 292.01, end: 297.59),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They pretend this isn't a real expense.", start: 298.17, end: 300.19),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But if you are an owner, it is a real expense—it dilutes your ownership stake.", start: 300.67, end: 304.89),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Consider the recent AI boom.", start: 305.67, end: 307.31),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "A company might show high EBITDA, but if they have to spend billions every year on new GPU clusters just to keep their model relevant, their Owner Earnings might be negative.", start: 307.89, end: 317.29),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They are running on a treadmill, running faster and faster just to stay in the same place.", start: 317.73, end: 322.31),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Capex Check: Open the Cash Flow Statement and compare \"Capital Expenditures\" (under Investing) to \"Depreciation\" (under Operating).", start: 323.13, end: 331.15),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If Capex is consistently higher than Depreciation, the company is burning cash just to stay alive rather than generating wealth for you—proceed with extreme caution.", start: 331.69, end: 341.15),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The \"Real\" P/E: Ignore the standard P/E ratio found on finance sites.", start: 341.97, end: 346.95),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Calculate \"Price to Free Cash Flow\" by dividing Market Cap by (Operating Cash Flow minus Capital Expenditures) to see the true multiple you are paying for the cash the business actually generates.", start: 347.43, end: 357.53),
                ]),
            ],
            3: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The \"Good Product\" Fallacy", start: 367.33, end: 368.91),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Here is the friction: most investors think a \"good company\" is one with a great product or a fast-growing market.", start: 369.67, end: 377.69),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They see a revolutionary technology or a popular brand and assume the stock is a winner.", start: 378.27, end: 383.81),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This is the \"Good Product Fallacy.\"", start: 384.49, end: 386.59),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "History is littered with companies that changed the world but went bankrupt because they couldn't protect their profits.", start: 387.33, end: 393.99),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you are buying a stock just because \"everyone is using it,\" you are missing the most critical variable: durability.", start: 394.67, end: 402.39),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "A castle with no moat is just a pile of gold waiting to be looted by competitors.", start: 403.09, end: 408.33),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Castle and the Knight", start: 409.44, end: 410.82),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Buffett solves this with his most famous metaphor: the \"Economic Moat.\"", start: 411.92, end: 416.28),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He asks you to imagine a business as a magnificent castle.", start: 416.94, end: 420.48),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Inside the castle is the \"Gold\"—the high returns on invested capital.", start: 421.14, end: 425.5),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But every day, a thousand knights (competitors) ride up to the castle walls, trying to steal that gold.", start: 426.06, end: 431.68),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He distinguishes between two types of businesses: \"Franchises\" and \"Commodities.\"", start: 432.7, end: 437.6),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "A Franchise is a castle with a wide, crocodile-filled moat.", start: 438.16, end: 442.1),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It has pricing power—it can raise prices, and customers still pay.", start: 442.62, end: 446.82),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Think of See's Candies, a company Buffett bought.", start: 447.5, end: 450.1),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They could raise the price of a box of chocolates every single year, and people would still buy it for Valentine's Day because no one wants to give their spouse \"discount\" chocolate.", start: 450.66, end: 460.38),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "A Commodity business, on the other hand, has no moat.", start: 461.04, end: 463.8),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It must compete solely on price.", start: 464.3, end: 466.42),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If it raises prices by a penny, customers leave.", start: 466.96, end: 469.76),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Buffett teaches that it is far better to buy a wonderful business (Franchise) at a fair price than a fair business (Commodity) at a wonderful price.", start: 470.42, end: 479.74),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The \"Network Effect\" Moat", start: 480.36, end: 481.88),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In the modern economy, moats have evolved from physical brands to digital networks.", start: 482.74, end: 488.48),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The most powerful moat today is the \"Network Effect\"—where a product becomes more valuable as more people use it.", start: 489.14, end: 496.4),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Consider the \"AI War.\"", start: 497.4, end: 498.94),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "A standalone AI wrapper app has a weak moat; anyone can copy the code and undercut the price.", start: 499.7, end: 506.21),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But a platform like the Apple App Store or Microsoft's enterprise ecosystem has a massive moat.", start: 506.89, end: 512.83),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you are a developer, you must be on the App Store because that's where the users are.", start: 513.57, end: 518.11),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you are a user, you stay because that's where the apps are.", start: 518.69, end: 521.89),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This creates a \"Switching Cost\" so high that users are effectively locked in.", start: 522.65, end: 527.35),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In the age of remote work and digital subscriptions, looking for high \"Switching Costs\" is the modern equivalent of looking for a brand name.", start: 528.23, end: 536.07),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If it takes a company 12 months and $10 million to migrate away from a software provider, that provider has a moat of steel.", start: 536.73, end: 544.35),
                ]),
            ],
            4: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Manic Neighbor", start: 559.07, end: 560.03),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You believe the market is an authority figure.", start: 561.09, end: 563.61),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "When a stock price collapses by 10% in a single morning, your primal brain assumes the market \"knows\" something you don’t.", start: 564.19, end: 571.87),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You feel foolish, exposed, and desperate to stop the pain.", start: 572.45, end: 576.33),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You assume price equals truth.", start: 577.11, end: 579.21),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But in the short run, the market is not a weighing machine that measures value; it is a voting machine that measures popularity.", start: 580.01, end: 587.49),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you let the daily ticker dictate your emotional state, you are letting a mob of strangers determine your self-worth.", start: 588.33, end: 595.15),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Legend of Mr. Market", start: 596.19, end: 597.75),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Buffett didn’t invent the solution to this; he inherited it from his mentor, Ben Graham, in the form of a parable that changes everything.", start: 598.75, end: 606.65),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Imagine you own a small business in partnership with a man named \"Mr.", start: 607.63, end: 611.61),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Market.\"", start: 611.65, end: 612.01),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Every single morning, without fail, Mr.", start: 612.69, end: 615.43),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Market knocks on your office door.", start: 615.47, end: 617.11),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He is a manic-depressive.", start: 617.89, end: 619.25),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Some days, he is euphoric, sees only sunshine, and offers to buy your share of the business for a ludicrously high price.", start: 619.83, end: 626.99),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Other days, he is despondent, sees only ruin, and offers to sell you his share for pennies on the dollar.", start: 627.71, end: 633.75),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The author teaches us that Mr.", start: 634.57, end: 636.29),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Market is there to serve you, not to guide you.", start: 636.37, end: 639.23),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "His wallet is open, but his wisdom is non-existent.", start: 639.83, end: 642.92),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You have three choices: you can ignore him, you can sell to him when he is manic, or you can buy from him when he is depressed.", start: 643.7, end: 650.82),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The one thing you must never do is fall under his influence.", start: 651.54, end: 654.94),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you look at a dropping price and think, \"I must be wrong,\" you have allowed the crazy neighbor to run your house.", start: 655.68, end: 661.88),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Algorithm Is the New Mr. Market", start: 662.36, end: 665.0),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In the 1950s, Mr.", start: 665.64, end: 667.6),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Market showed up once a day in the morning newspaper.", start: 667.66, end: 670.92),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Today, he lives in your pocket, screaming at you 24/7 through push notifications and red/green candlesticks.", start: 671.66, end: 680.0),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Modern apps have gamified this manic behavior.", start: 681.1, end: 684.1),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They use bright red colors and downward arrows to trigger a cortisol spike (fear) and bright green confetti to trigger dopamine (greed).", start: 684.78, end: 694.46),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In the world of Crypto and 24-hour trading, Mr.", start: 695.24, end: 698.76),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Market never sleeps; he is on a permanent bender.", start: 698.82, end: 702.02),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you check your portfolio five times a day, you are inviting a manic-depressive into your brain five times a day to scream at you.", start: 702.88, end: 711.18),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The \"wiser\" investor realizes that volatility is not risk—it is the fee you pay for entrance.", start: 712.08, end: 718.74),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you can decouple your mood from the color of the pixels on your screen, you have an insurmountable advantage over the algorithm-addicted masses.", start: 719.48, end: 728.5),
                ]),
            ],
            5: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The CEO’s Secret Addiction", start: 735.7, end: 737.6),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Here is the friction: You assume the CEO works for you.", start: 738.64, end: 742.74),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "You assume their primary goal is to make your shares more valuable.", start: 743.4, end: 747.22),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In reality, most CEOs suffer from a \"growth addiction.\"", start: 747.96, end: 752.08),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Their salaries, prestige, and magazine covers are often tied to the size of the company (total revenue), not the value per share.", start: 752.76, end: 761.2),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This creates a conflict of interest.", start: 761.82, end: 763.48),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "A CEO will often take the cash the business generates—your cash—and light it on fire by buying a mediocre competitor at a premium price, just to make the empire bigger.", start: 764.1, end: 775.13),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They call it \"strategic synergy.\"", start: 775.73, end: 777.61),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Usually, it’s just ego.", start: 778.29, end: 779.61),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If you don't watch how management spends the money in the bank, you are letting a teenager with a credit card run your household.", start: 780.37, end: 786.75),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The \"One Dollar\" Ultimatum", start: 787.61, end: 789.23),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Buffett counters this with a ruthless rule known as the \"One Dollar Test.\"", start: 790.47, end: 794.67),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In his letters, he lays out a simple ultimatum for management: A company should only retain earnings if, for every dollar retained, it creates at least one dollar of market value over time.", start: 795.33, end: 807.07),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He tells the story of how easy it is for a CEO to \"buy\" growth.", start: 807.71, end: 812.09),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Anyone can grow sales by buying a bad business.", start: 812.75, end: 815.33),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But a true \"Capital Allocator\" (Buffett's highest praise) knows when to shrink.", start: 815.81, end: 820.65),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If the company cannot reinvest cash at a high rate of return, the CEO must have the humility to give it back to the shareholders—either through dividends (a direct check) or share buybacks (increasing your percentage of ownership).", start: 821.37, end: 834.41),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He views a share buyback not as a market signal, but as a way to buy out \"unhappy partners\" at a discount, instantly making the remaining partners richer without them lifting a finger.", start: 835.07, end: 845.41),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Buyback Masquerade", start: 845.87, end: 847.55),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In the modern tech era, the \"Share Buyback\" has been corrupted.", start: 848.19, end: 851.99),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Many Silicon Valley giants announce massive, multi-billion dollar buyback programs to great fanfare.", start: 852.55, end: 858.73),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It sounds like they are returning capital to you.", start: 859.31, end: 861.65),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Often, they are lying.", start: 862.38, end: 863.68),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They are using those buybacks to offset \"Stock-Based Compensation\" (SBC).", start: 864.24, end: 868.6),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "They pay their engineers in millions of new shares (diluting you), then use company cash to buy those shares back (undiluting you).", start: 869.38, end: 877.52),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The net result?", start: 878.04, end: 878.64),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The share count stays flat, but the cash is gone.", start: 879.12, end: 882.08),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This is running in place.", start: 882.54, end: 884.0),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "A \"wiser\" analysis looks at the net change in share count.", start: 884.62, end: 888.22),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If a company spends $10 billion on buybacks but the share count doesn't drop, that wasn't a return of capital—it was a disguised employee salary expense.", start: 888.86, end: 897.82),
                ]),
            ],
            6: [
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Boardroom Blind Spot", start: 910.94, end: 912.52),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We treat CEOs like chess grandmasters.", start: 913.5, end: 916.16),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We assume that when a leader announces a massive acquisition or a pivot into a new technology, they have run thousands of simulations and found the optimal move.", start: 916.74, end: 925.86),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "But inside the boardroom, a different, darker game is being played.", start: 926.86, end: 930.62),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "It isn’t strategy; it’s survival.", start: 931.34, end: 933.38),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Most corporate leadership is not driven by logic, but by a terrifying fear of being the \"odd one out.\"", start: 934.38, end: 940.28),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If Competitor A buys a blockchain startup, Competitor B feels a primal compulsion to buy one too, regardless of the price.", start: 941.16, end: 948.06),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If they don't, and blockchain succeeds, they look like fools.", start: 948.69, end: 951.59),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If they buy it and it fails, well, \"everyone else did it too.\"", start: 952.17, end: 955.03),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "This herd mentality is the single greatest destroyer of shareholder capital, yet it parades itself as \"industry standard best practice.\"", start: 955.97, end: 963.99),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The \"Institutional Imperative\"", start: 964.85, end: 966.67),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Buffett coined a specific term for this force: the \"Institutional Imperative.\"", start: 967.63, end: 971.97),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In his letters, he dissects how decent, intelligent managers turn into irrational copycats the moment they enter a corporate hierarchy.", start: 972.85, end: 980.43),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He compares it to a teenager smoking to look cool.", start: 981.35, end: 983.67),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The Imperative dictates that if an investment banker proposes a deal, the CEO will find a way to justify it.", start: 984.49, end: 990.17),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "If a competitor expands, the CEO will expand.", start: 990.97, end: 993.65),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Buffett famously noted that this force is so strong it can make a group of brilliant people do things that any one of them, acting alone, would call insane.", start: 994.51, end: 1002.15),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "He teaches us that the rarest asset in business is not intelligence—it is the courage to say \"no\" when everyone else is shouting \"yes.\"", start: 1002.87, end: 1010.05),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: true, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "The \"Pivot\" Pandemic", start: 1010.99, end: 1012.05),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "In the modern era, the Institutional Imperative has accelerated into a virus.", start: 1012.91, end: 1016.77),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "We see it in the \"Pivot\" culture.", start: 1017.27, end: 1018.61),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "First, it was the \"Dot-com\" pivot.", start: 1019.17, end: 1021.39),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Then, the \"Blockchain\" pivot.", start: 1021.97, end: 1023.51),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Now, it is the \"AI\" pivot.", start: 1024.15, end: 1026.01),
                    ReadAlongSentence(text: "Companies that sell pet food or furniture have no business declaring themselves \"AI-first\" organizations, yet they launch half-baked chatbots just to boost their stock price for a quarter.", start: 1026.77, end: 1037.98),
                ]),
                ReadAlongBlock(isHeading: false, sentences: [
